<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Hits Japanese Islands  </HEADLINE>
By ERIC PRIDEAUX
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A strong earthquake jolted a string of Japanese
islands off Tokyo Saturday, slightly injuring at least two people,
damaging buildings and forcing hundreds to evacuate. The quake hit
hours after a volcano in the chain erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude 6.2 quake Saturday morning knocked down the walls
of several homes and caused power outages on Niijima island, about
105 miles south of the capital, said local official Sojiro
Miyakawa.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was among thousands that have hit the islands in
recent weeks. On July 1, a magnitude 6.4 earthquake killed a
fisherman in a car that was buried under fallen rocks on Kozushima.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 residents on Niijima were evacuating to safer areas,
said Noboru Tomita, another island official. They were traveling by
boat, as the main road was blocked by debris from landslides.
</P>
<P>
   Two people were slightly injured, said Tomita. Kyodo News agency
identified them as a 61-year-old woman and a 52-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   Television footage showed boulders dislodged from a mountainside
resting precariously close to homes in a village on Niijima.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori was meeting with a team of
crisis-response officials, national broadcaster NHK said.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn on Saturday, a volcano on the island of Miyakejima
erupted for the fifth time in a week, spewing ash and forcing more
than 100 people to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   The eruption of the 2,670-foot Mount Oyama shot gray ash as high
as 600 yards into the sky, the meteorological agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's biggest eruption coughed up a pillar of dark smoke
1,500 yards high, creating a blizzard of whirling ash that engulfed
cars and homes on the northern part of the island below.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders have complained of mental fatigue caused by the
constant tremors. Miyakejima, home to about 4,000 people, and the
nearby islands have been rocked by more than 17,500 earthquakes in
recent weeks, including about 5,480 that are strong enough to be
felt by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, 502 people from a hot-spring resort near an active
volcano in northern Japan were allowed to return home Friday after
102 days of evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The families were among more than 13,000 people evacuated in
March, when Mount Usu erupted for the first time in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many have been allowed to return home. But 1,432 people are
still staying at public facilities or at relatives' homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 0052 </TRAILER>
