<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Umpires Support Valentine Ejection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Mets manager Bobby Valentine should have been
ejected during the seventh inning of New York's 6-4 win over Boston
on Friday night, umpire Randy Marsh admitted after the game.
</P>
<P>
   During a wild seventh inning, both benches emptied when Mets'
catcher Todd Pratt and Boston batter Brian Daubach had words,
following Daubach asking for time when Dennis Cook was on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Cook appeared to take a long time before making a move to throw
a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Both benches and bullpens emptied, but no punches were thrown.
Home plate umpire Marty Foster clearly issued a warning to both
benches before the next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   On the following pitch, Daubach singled to right, tying the game
at 3. Two pitches later, Cook hit Carl Everett and was ejected by
Foster.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rule 8.02 Sec. D-2, both the pitcher and manager
should have been ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Probably, technically, yes,'' said Marsh, the second base
umpire and crew chief. ''Technically, the manager should have been.
(Foster) was trying to get control in that situation. He got (Cook)
out, that's the important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon being asked about the rule, Marsh said: ''(The ejection)
probably should have happened in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was clearly on the bench for the remainder of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was never told I was being ejected,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Valentine was ejected from a game, and came back
later with a fake mustache and glasses, and sat on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, Boston manager Jimy Williams was ejected after
Pedro Martinez hit Roberto Alomar, following a warning to both
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''The same thing happened to me in Cleveland,'' Williams said
after Friday's game. ''I didn't see (Valentine). He's supposed to
be ejected automatically. That's my understanding of the rule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
