<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma Gov. Eyed For GOP V.P.  </HEADLINE>
By TIM TALLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Millions of Americans got to know Oklahoma
Gov. Frank Keating on TV as a spokesman for his state after the
carnage of the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was able to put a face to that very tragic situation,''
says political consultant Neva Hill. ''He was a person who could
help bring some focus and steadiness at the helm.''
</P>
<P>
   That could serve him well as fellow Republican Gov. George W.
Bush goes about his search for a presidential running mate. By all
accounts, Keating is on Bush's list.
</P>
<P>
   But the words Keating uses in political spats back home
sometimes get him into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   He has described bad teachers as ''slugs'' and has compared
growing up as a Catholic in Tulsa to being a black in Selma, Ala.,
during the 1960s, angering some blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a reputation of shooting from the lip,'' said Don
Hoover, a Democratic media consultant in Oklahoma City. ''If he is
selected, he will have the national spotlight shine on him like it
never has before. I don't think it's going to reflect on him
favorably.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says veteran Republican political consultant Marc
Nuttle. ''He appeals to a broad range of people across state lines
and regions. He's the candidate who can appeal to the swing voter
and galvanize the base,'' says Nuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, 56, has been low-key about a vice-presidential future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't expect it to happen,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   But the pluses are there. He's Catholic and anti-abortion. He
supports the death penalty. And his crime-fighting reputation,
pro-business, tax-cutting agenda and aggressive campaign style
could complement Bush on a GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A former FBI agent and federal prosecutor, Keating worked in the
administrations of Presidents Reagan and Bush as assistant
secretary of the treasury and associate attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he became general counsel and acting deputy secretary
of the Department of Housing and Urban Development under Jack Kemp,
who credited Keating for helping clean up the agency that was
embroiled in scandal in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush nominated Keating to the 10th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals. But the NAACP opposed the nomination, alleging he had
undercut fair housing laws and had made racially insensitive
remarks. The nomination was blocked by Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Keating and Bush have developed a close relationship while
serving as the chief executives of adjoining states. The governors
and their wives have visited with each other, occasionally dining
together, said Dan Mahoney, Keating's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has other friends in high places. Keating's former
secretary of state and a top political strategist, Tom Cole, is
chief of staff for the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Keating has been criticized by teachers for supporting
tax vouchers for private schools and other education changes. But
in February he signed a $168 million teacher pay raise bill -- the
largest in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Keating was accused of being an elitist when he called on state
lawmakers to pass reforms ''to make us rich.'' Although an avowed
fiscal conservative, Keating developed a road program that will
invest $3 billion in highway and turnpike construction.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's probably been the biggest borrow-and-spend governor that
Oklahoma has ever had,'' says Democrat Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   And recently he has had to explain a fishing trip he took to
Alaska, that was paid for by the Conoco Co. He said it was to drum
up business, adding: ''I will go anywhere and do anything to enrich
my state.'' ... That is ''what chief executives should do.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent state Democrat, Gordon Melson, ridiculed it as ''a
trip by a bunch of Republican pals to have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he's tapped to be vice president, political
pundits expect Keating to go places in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''His attributes are organization, discipline, a great ability
to include everyone in decision making even though he has strong
instincts,'' says former boss Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Keating should be a help on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ''He likes pressing the flesh,'' says Hill, the Oklahoma City
consultant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
