<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Battles Deluge of Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By THAKSINA KHAIKAEW
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAN MAE LA NA, Thailand (AP) -- In its opium-growing days, this
mountain village was the target of a campaign to wipe out
narcotics. Now its residents, rifles in hand, are helping wage
Thailand's latest war on drugs -- against a deluge of
methamphetamines and heroin from neighboring Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   As in other areas of the so-called ''Golden Triangle'' in
Thailand, fields where colorful but deadly opium poppies once
bloomed have been converted to rice, soybean and corn cultivation
under a successful foreign-aided effort.
</P>
<P>
   ''Domestic drug supply has been stopped, but the menace persists
because supplies keep coming from next-door Myanmar,'' says
Phornchai Khamkhiew, headman of this frontier village astride a
narcotics smuggling route. ''We can't let problems brought in by
outsiders ruin our community.''
</P>
<P>
   In one attempt to halt the inflow across a long, rugged and
porous border, the Thai army has trained villagers in 29 remote
areas to take up weapons against the traffickers. Fifteen men at
Ban Mae La Na, 404 miles northwest of the Thai capital Bangkok,
have been trained to use weapons and patrol the forests.
</P>
<P>
   Their chief opponent is the United Wa State Army, described by
the United States as the world's largest drug-trafficking
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Wa guerrillas mass-produce heroin, which is
synthesized from poppies, and methamphetamines in laboratories
inside Myanmar and speed their penetration into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Western Europe and others in the world
community are deeply concerned because much of the heroin makes its
way through Thailand to addicts on their own streets. The Thais,
while also battling heroin, are focusing on methamphetamines,
widely abused by everyone from wealthy teen-agers to slum dwellers
and poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Narcotics Control Board estimates that 600 million
of the speed pills, worth $1.2 billion, have been smuggled into
Thailand from Myanmar this year.
</P>
<P>
   It places the number of just teen-age abusers at some 260,000,
and the cost to Thai society in suppression and medical treatment
at more than $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Trafficking in and abuse of methamphetamines have become
Thailand's top drug problem in recent years, supplanting heroin,''
said Pol. Lt. Gen. Komrit Patpongpanich, the top anti-narcotics
cop, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. drug officials have also warned of increasing use of meth,
which can be made from legal chemicals, in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of drugs has severely strained relations between
Thailand and Myanmar's ruling military. The U.S. State Department
says Myanmar is the world's no. 2 producer of illegal narcotics,
after Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar, also known as Burma, says it is trying to fight drugs
but gets very little foreign aid to help it.
</P>
<P>
   Thai officials believe a relocation early this year of some
50,000 Myanmar people who lived in prime opium-growing areas near
the Chinese border controlled by the Wa to a region near Thailand
has increased cross-border trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know what the problem is, but can't go across the
border to get rid of the source,'' said Lt. Gen. Wattanachai
Chaimuanwongse, who heads narcotics suppression in northern
Thailand, which together with adjacent areas of Laos and Myanmar
forms the drug-drenched ''Golden Triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although gunbattles with Myanmar traffickers and Thai pushers
are not uncommon, Wattanachai and others stress that force will
never win the war. Also needed is diplomatic effort with Myanmar,
cooperation with villagers along trafficking routes and domestic
social programs to stop addiction.
</P>
<P>
   A recent drug raid in Bangkok illustrated the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn, 30 armed plainclothes policemen and three sniffer
dogs, accompanied by an Associated Press reporter, scoured a fetid
slum known to be awash in drugs and pills.
</P>
<P>
   ''My younger brother was an addict but he quit several months
ago,'' said Arunee Yodpet, 29, when the police barged into her home
but came away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This community is full of drug abusers and pushers,'' she
added. ''I tell my young son not to go and play far from the house
because I'm afraid that someone might give him pills to try.''
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down, the police finally made a seizure -- three pink
pills -- and hauled away a 21-year-old suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ''Methamphetamine abuse is widespread in Bangkok's slums. Poor
people take it to escape from the hardship in daily life,'' said
one of the raiders. ''Suppression alone is not enough to solve the
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
