<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canadian Tornado Kills at Least 5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PINE LAKE, Alberta (AP) -- At least five people were killed and 38 others
were injured Friday night when a tornado touched down at a campground in the
western Canadian province of Alberta, officials said. Several hundred trailers
had been flipped upside down at the Green Acres campground and a stream of tow
trucks, ambulances, rescue divers and other emergency services were descending
on the site, about 90 miles north of Calgary. The numbers of dead and wounded
''are obviously not final yet,'' said Jim Squire, spokesman for Red Deer County.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Strong Quake Hits Japanese Islands
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A strong earthquake jolted a string of Japanese islands off
Tokyo Saturday, slightly injuring at least two people, damaging buildings and
forcing hundreds to evacuate. The quake hit hours after a volcano in the chain
erupted. The magnitude 6.2 quake Saturday morning knocked down the walls of
several homes and caused power outages on Niijima island, about 105 miles south
of the capital, said local official Sojiro Miyakawa. The quake was among
thousands that have hit the islands in recent weeks. On July 1, a magnitude 6.4
earthquake killed a fisherman in a car that was buried under fallen rocks on
Kozushima.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tobacco Cos. Told To Pay Billions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A jury took less than five hours to decide that the tobacco
industry should pay a record-shattering $145 billion in punitive damages to sick
Florida smokerson Friday -- an amount industry lawyers predicted would break the
industry. Stock prices of the five companies were down moderately following the
two-year ruling. The companies plan to appeal, and the verdict will likely be
tied up in the appeals process for years and is not expected to have any
immediate impact on the industry.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury: Govt. Not Liable in Waco
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- An advisory jury decided Friday that the government does
not bear responsibility for the deaths of 80 Branch Davidians during the cult's
1993 standoff with federal agents. A federal judge will deliver the final
verdict. The five jurors deliberated for 2&AMP;frac12; hours in the $675 million
wrongful-death lawsuit filed by surviving Branch Davidians and relatives of
those who were killed. The trial, which lasted nearly a month, brought out
emotional testimony recounting the standoff from both sides.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AIDS Conference Focuses on Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) -- The high-profile International AIDS Conference,
held for the first time at ground zero of the epidemic, ended Friday as it
began, dominated as much by questions of money and political will as of
medicine. More than 12,000 people from around the world came together for a week
to look for solutions to an epidemic that now infects 34 million people on the
planet, 95 percent of them in the poorest regions, especially sub-Saharan
Africa. While some of those at the conference spoke of cutting-edge research
into new drugs most of the attention was on the much more basic need to prevent
the explosive spread of the virus in countries with the fewest resources.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former Starr Aide on Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former independent counsel aide Charles Bakaly III
admitted to the FBI that he played ''a risky game'' by cooperating with a New
York Times reporter, but he also tried to help investigators find the sources
for news leaks, two agents testified at his contempt trial Friday. One agent
revealed Bakaly told him about a straw vote by prosecutors on whether to indict
the president. Agents Thomas Lewis and Michael Erbach were among the
investigators searching for the anonymous ''associates'' of then-Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr, who were quoted in a Jan. 31, 1999 Times article.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
	   Dow Ends Up 24; Nasdaq Is Up 71
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed aside a landmark ruling against the
tobacco industry Friday, pushing stock prices higher after new government data
showed inflationary pressures remain under control. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed up 24.04 at 10,812.75. On the NYSE, gainers edged losers by a
7-to-6 margin. The Nasdaq composite index was up 71.32 at 4,246.18.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Diamondbacks Beat Rangers 6-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Steve Finley homered, tripled and drove in four runs and
Armando Reynoso pitched a six-hitter as the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the Texas
Rangers 6-1 on Friday night. Jay Bell added an RBI double for the Diamondbacks,
who snapped a three-game losing streak against the Rangers. Royce Clayton hit
his 14th homer for Texas. Reynoso (6-6) struck out five, walked none and at one
point retired eight straight hitters in pitching his seventh career complete
game.
</P>
