<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 07:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Slide Survivors Promised Homes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- Officials promised money and new housing
Saturday for survivors of a landslide that buried a Bombay
shantytown, killing at least 74 people.
</P>
<P>
   But, skeptical of the promises, some 140 survivors worried about
how to rebuild their lives after losing everything in the mud and
boulders that barreled down on their shacks Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yasin Ahmed, a car mechanic who survived the landslide along
with his wife, brother and two sons, said doctors told him his
fractured arm will take three weeks to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ''What will my family eat till then? My brother and I are the
only breadwinners,'' Ahmed, 28, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The state government of Maharashtra, of which Bombay is capital,
has promised $220 to each injured person and $550 to relatives of
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a terrible, terrible tragedy. The government will
provide houses to the victims,'' said Sonia Gandhi, president of
the Congress Party, which is in power in the state. On Saturday,
Gandhi flew into Bombay to visit the injured at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Some 140 survivors from the Azad Nagar shantytown are scattered
in nearby schools and hospitals that have been converted into
temporary relief camps.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them do odd jobs at construction sites. Like millions of
other poor migrants who arrive in Bombay in search of a better
life, these laborers built illegal homes out of mud and tin atop a
hill.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of free houses is the only ray of hope for them. But
people like Nafisa Nasibi are not convinced. Nasibi, a housewife,
is still recovering from the shock of losing her husband and
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''People come here and promise all kinds of things. Who knows
what we will get once these VIPs leave,'' said Nasibi, who sat
beside her 8-year-old son, who was hospitalized with a head injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even if we do get a place to live, I don't know what I will do
about work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first night after the landslide, no bodies were
retrieved from the debris Saturday, diminishing hopes of any
survivors. Local residents estimated some 40 people were missing
and feared they could be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal authorities said they were preparing a list of
families who would be given free houses. ''The immediate need is to
provide them with houses during the rains. The rest we can look
after later,'' said Pravin Chheda, a city council member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
