<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Rescue Mission Launched  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- The United Nations launched a
military operation Saturday to rescue some 220 peacekeepers and 11
military observers trapped inside a U.N. base in a rebel stronghold
in eastern Sierra Leone, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The military rescue operation is currently going on,'' the
United Nations said in a statement delivered to journalists in
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers, mainly Indian soldiers, had been unable to
leave their base inside rebel Revolutionary United Front
headquarters of Kailahun, some 185 miles east of Freetown, since
May. The detained soldiers still had their weapons but over the
past two weeks the rebels refused to allow the U.N. force in Sierra
Leone, known as UNAMSIL, to send them food supplies by road or air.
</P>
<P>
   Recent torrential rains had also limited the detained
peacekeepers' ability to move, the statement added. The U.N.
soldiers were in a base measuring 500 by 500 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. rescue team consisted of troops from Ghana, India and
Nigeria, the statement said. U.N. force commander Indian Maj. Gen.
Vijay Jetley was personally overseeing the mission from a nearby
U.N. base in the town of Daru, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a distress signal received from (the detained troops in)
Kailahun, regarding the dwindling food and medical stocks, there
was no alternative to a military option,'' the statement said.
''The RUF's illegal actions, which have been universally condemned
and for which appeals had been made by UNAMSIL to the RUF for quick
resolution, yielded no results.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels reignited Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war in May
by launching attacks on towns and capturing some 500 U.N. hostages,
who were later released after being disarmed and held for several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have systematically killed and maimed tens of
thousands of innocent civilians in a bid to gain power through
fear. During the war, they abandoned three different peace accords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 0744 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
