<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Peacekeepers Rescued  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- A U.N. military operation Saturday
rescued all 220 peacekeepers and 11 military observers trapped by
rebels inside a U.N. base in eastern Sierra Leone, a U.N.
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The 220 detained Indian troops, who had been unable to leave the
rebel-held town of Kailahun since May, were liberated by a U.N.
military team and were on their way by road to the nearby town of
Daru, said the spokeswoman, Hirut Befecadu.
</P>
<P>
   The group had met no resistance so far, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 military observers, from various countries, were flown by
helicopter to Freetown, Befecadu said.
</P>
<P>
   No other details were immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. statement delivered to journalists earlier Saturday
morning said the U.N. rescue team consisted of troops from Ghana,
India and Nigeria. U.N. force commander Indian Maj. Gen. Vijay
Jetley was personally overseeing the mission from a nearby U.N.
base in the town of Daru, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The detained peacekeepers still had their weapons but over the
past two weeks the rebels refused to allow the U.N. force in Sierra
Leone, known as UNAMSIL, to send them food supplies by road or air.
</P>
<P>
   Recent torrential rains had also limited the detained
peacekeepers' ability to move, the statement added. The U.N.
soldiers were in a base measuring 500 by 500 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a distress signal received from (the detained troops in)
Kailahun, regarding the dwindling food and medical stocks, there
was no alternative to a military option,'' the statement said.
''The RUF's illegal actions, which have been universally condemned
and for which appeals had been made by UNAMSIL to the RUF for quick
resolution, yielded no results.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels reignited Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war in May
by launching attacks on towns and capturing some 500 U.N. hostages,
who were later released after being disarmed and held for several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have systematically killed and maimed tens of
thousands of innocent civilians in a bid to gain power through
fear. During the war, the renegades abandoned three different peace
accords including the latest signed in July last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 0811 </TRAILER>
