<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Serbs Make Concessions  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a widening split over Kosovo's
first internationally supervised elections, moderate Serbs say they
are willing to participate if some conditions are met, while their
hardline counterparts insist on a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday had been the deadline for Kosovars of all groups --
Albanian, Serb, Turkish, Gypsies and others -- to register for
municipal elections in October. However, U.N. administrator Bernard
Kouchner extended the deadline until the close of business
Wednesday after international officials said they had seen the
first clear signs that some Kosovo Serbs wanted to take part.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was decided to give them time to see whether those
indications produce something tangible,'' said Roland Bless,
spokesman for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe which will supervise the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Serb
community in the small town of Leposavic was interested in
registering.
</P>
<P>
   And in Gracanica, just south of Pristina, a group representing
the province's moderate Serb faction said late Friday that they
would not boycott the vote in areas ''where there is a minimum of
conditions that municipal authorities actually function.''
</P>
<P>
   Backing of elections by the moderates is conditional on U.N.
agreement that no voting take place in areas where a fair ballot is
impossible because of a ''lack of human rights,'' said a statement
carried by the Beta news agency
</P>
<P>
   However, Serb leaders in the largest Serb enclave, Kosovska
Mitrovica, remained adamantly opposed. The Serb leader there,
Oliver Ivanovic, wants the United Nations to return 1,500 Serbs
within one week from Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Serbs fled the province after Yugoslav troops
withdrew in June 1999 following the 78-day NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic has also insisted that the United Nations provide a
concrete timetable for organizing the return of another 210,000
non-Albanians who fled Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   However, U.N. officials have been resisting the demand. The
outgoing Kosovo chief of the U.N. refugee agency, Dennis McNamara,
said a premature return of Serbs would only worsen the already
tense ethnic climate in the province.
</P>
<P>
   After the U.N. announcement Friday, the official Yugoslav news
agency Tanjug quoted the hardline Serb National Council as ruling
out any possibility of Serbs taking part in registration and
elections until Serbs who fled last year can return.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Serbs from this region will not register nor take part in
the vote until Serbs start returning to Kosovo in bigger numbers,''
said Dragisa Milovic, spokesman for Ivanovic.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the international community succeeds in organizing the
return of the Serbs, guaranteeing their safety, we will change our
minds,'' Milovic added. ''For now, we have absolutely no security
in Kosovo, nor are we able to move around. Under those conditions,
any election would be absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders of the 15,000-strong Turkish minority were also
boycotting to press demands that the Turkish language be considered
equal under the law with Albanian and Serbian province-wide. Only
about 1,000 ethnic Turks had registered by late Friday, the OSCE
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without significant minority participation, the U.N. idea of
elections as a basis of creating a democratic multiethnic community
would be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians are believed to comprise more than 90 percent
of Kosovo's estimated 2 million people, although no reliable census
has been taken in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ambassador to the United Nations, Sergey Lavrov, has
challenged the decision to proceed with the October election
without major Serb participation. Lavrov told the U.N. Security
Council on Thursday that lack of participation by the Serbs ''would
distort both the ethnic and the political picture in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Assistant Secretary-General Hedi Annabi told the Council
that virtually all the registration applications -- which the United
Nations here said has reached 1 million -- were from ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, U.N. spokeswoman Susan Manuel said in Pristina
that the Russian objections were ''not going to influence our plans
for holding elections in October. We will have elections in
October.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
