<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group: China Farmers, Police Clash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Farmers worried that the government planned to
block access to a reservoir fought with police in drought-stricken
eastern China in a clash that left an officer dead and 140 people
injured, a rights group reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation July 6 highlights an increasingly dire
shortage of water in northern China. Drought this year has already
destroyed 35 million acres of crops and left 16.2 million people
short of water, nearly a fifth of them in eastern Shandong
province.
</P>
<P>
   Officials concerned about protecting the Mushan reservoir, one
of Shandong's largest, decided in recent weeks to start a project
to prevent seepage, the Hong Kong-based Information Center of Human
Rights and Democracy reported.
</P>
<P>
   That alarmed farmers who had long relied on the seepage to
irrigate their fields, and 5,000 farmers blocked construction of
the project July 6, the center said.
</P>
<P>
   They fought with 300 police sent to disperse them, and 100
farmers and 40 officers were wounded, the center said. It added
that one officer was beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Mushan reservoir management bureau and the
nearby Anqiu city government confirmed that a clash happened, but
either contradicted or refused to comment on details of the
Information Center account.
</P>
<P>
   One official with the Anqiu propaganda department, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the farmers tried to break into the
reservoir management bureau, fighting with its officials, not
police.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid development in the countryside has caused frequent
disputes between farmers and officials over land-use rights, with
some resulting in protests. The Information Center said nationwide
China had 100,000 protests last year, up from 60,000 in 1998. All
but a few go unreported by state-controlled media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
