<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco tax hike a ''disaster'' to cigarette vendors  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The near doubling of New York's cigarette
tax to a highest-in-the-nation $1.11 a pack has been a ''disaster''
for small retailers, the state Association of Convenience Stores
says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tobacco taxes were being paid to the state at a
rate about 25 percent lower for the first four months the new tax
was in effect than in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Stores are reporting drop-offs in cigarette sales of between 30
percent and 60 percent since March 1 when the state added 55 cents
a pack onto the old 56-cent-a-pack cigarette tax, according to Jim
Calvin, executive director of the Albany-based convenience stores
association.
</P>
<P>
   Since cigarettes are typically the stores' single biggest
sellers, accounting for a quarter to a third of income, the slump
in tobacco sales is pinching vendors, Calvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hurting them, without a doubt,'' agreed Mark Alesse, head
of the state chapter of the National Federation of Independent
Business. ''They are seeing sales drop off, particularly stores
near Indian reservations. They're getting killed and they don't
know what to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian vendors do not charge sales tax on cigarettes, so they
can offer cartons to customers for as much as $13.50 less than
non-Indian retailers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to non-Indian vendors in western and central New
York, Calvin said New York retailers close to the state's 340-mile
border with Pennsylvania are also suffering. Cigarette taxes in
that state are only 31 cents a pack, meaning New York smokers can
save $8 a carton by venturing into Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin said he doubts that anything like a quarter to a third of
the smokers in New York have quit because of the tax price hike.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it were a case of people gradually quitting smoking, I
think our industry could adapt to that,'' he said. ''But the loss
of business has occurred overnight and you will never convince me
that that many people quit smoking that fast all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette tax increase was approved by the Legislature and
Gov. George Pataki in December. Part of the revenue from the
increased tax is earmarked for a state health insurance program for
the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco advocates predicted that the ''sticker shock'' on
tobacco prices produced by the tax increase would also cause some
people to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues to the state under the higher tobacco tax rate were up
- $303.8 million from March through June of this year vs. $209.6
million for the similar period last year.
</P>
<P>
   But that takes into an account the near doubling of the tax. Had
the rate of payments remained steady under the higher tax, the
state would have collected roughly $400 million during that same
period instead of the $303.8 million it did take in.
</P>
<P>
   Under another comparison, the state is continuing to bank the
''old'' portion of the tobacco tax, the 56-cent-a-pack charge, and
is channeling the ''new'' add-on to pay for health programs.
According to state Comptroller H. Carl McCall's office, the 56-cent
portion of the tax totaled $154.6 million for March through June of
this year, or nearly $57.5 million less than the tax of the same
amount accounted for during March through June of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Baker, who manages seven Taylor's Mini Mart stores in the
Cooperstown area, said cigarette sales in her stores are down about
30 percent since the new tax took effect. That does not count the
loss of other business that customers who smoke tend to bring to
the stores, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Typical nonsmokers will spend about $1.25 per visit to one of
her stores, according to Baker. Smokers, who are often daily
customers, will spend on average more than $5.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Newman, whose company operates 50 Noco Express and
Express Shop stores in the Buffalo area, said his shops' cigarette
sales are down 32 percent since March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Pataki) thinks he is preventing smoking by doing this, but
what he is doing is driving smokers to the reservations. ... What
he has done is create a smoker's paradise on the reservations and
subsequently is costing tax revenues to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin said tobacco retail industry officials warned state
leaders that a dramatic increase in the cigarette tax would not
have the intended effects.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been a disaster,'' he said. ''It has backfired. It is
neither dissuading people from smoking nor generating the revenues
it was intended to generate to fund health care programs. But it
has most certainly severely impacted the convenience store industry
- which is comprised mainly of mom-and-pop operations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-15-00 1214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000715.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki rakes in almost $2.35 million in first half of year  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki collected almost $2.35
million during the first six months of this year to prepare for a
possible bid for a third term in 2002, aides reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The show of fund-raising muscle is opportune for Pataki. The New
York Republican is considered a possible running mate for George W.
Bush in the Texas governor's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, as Pataki geared up for his successful bid for a
second, four-year term as governor, his campaign committee
collected $1.66 million during the first six months of that year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a Democrat
considering a run for governor in 2002, reported raising more than
$1.1 million in the first six months of this year. McCall, in a
report prepared for filing with the state Board of Elections, said
that after expenses, he still had more than $1.05 million in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, after spending almost $667,000 during the first six
months of this year, still has $3.97 million in his campaign
account, according to his report.
</P>
<P>
   ''This clearly shows an enormous amount of support for Governor
Pataki's policies and for his record of achievement in this
state,'' said Pataki spokeswoman Zenia Mucha.
</P>
<P>
   Mucha, one of the governor's top political advisers, said
Pataki's campaign used direct-mail appeals heavily in the latest
fund-raising period and managed to generate about 4,000 new
contributors as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki aide said the money could not be legally used for a
vice presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Pataki has routinely demonstrated an ability to put
together large campaign bankrolls quickly and his latest success
comes at a time when Bush and Vice President Al Gore are mining New
York heavily for campaign cash, as are U.S. Senate candidates
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican Rep. Rick Lazio. Lazio's GOP
predecessor in the Senate race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, had
collected almost $20 million through the end of March. The New York
City mayor left the race in mid-May in the face of prostate cancer
and marital problems.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has told supporters in private meetings that he will run
for governor, but for public consumption he has said only that he
would like to run. McCall has promised an announcement about his
plans soon after this November's election for president and U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Besides McCall, federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, the
eldest son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo, is considering a run for the
Democratic nomination for governor. The younger Cuomo has not yet
begun fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Running for governor in New York state has become an expensive
proposition. In 1998, Pataki spent more than $20 million to win a
second term. At this point four years ago, Pataki reported almost
$2.85 million in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six months of last year, Pataki reported raising
more than $824,000 and started this year with $2.32 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-15-00 1223 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000715.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin: Reassert Russian Power  </HEADLINE>
By JIM HEINTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's economy may be overshadowed by those of
the seven richest industrial nations, but President Vladimir Putin
aims to keep Russia in the spotlight at next week's Group of Eight
summit.
</P>
<P>
   By making high-profile stops in China and North Korea en route
to the summit, Putin will try to bolster Russia's image as a world
power, then follow up by using the summit to push Russia's global
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Russia began its connection with the Group of Seven major
industrial democracies -- the United States, Canada, Britain,
Germany, France, Italy and Japan -- in 1997. President Clinton
invited then-President Boris Yeltsin to attend a G-7 summit that
year as an inducement for Russia to back off from objections to
NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation was attractive to the country that once cherished
its superpower status, but then watched it decay with the collapse
of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Group of Seven still holds separate economic
meetings, Russia appears marginalized. Summits such as the one
beginning July 21 in Okinawa, Japan, are often seen as meetings of
the Group of Seven-Plus-One instead of eight equal partners.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia will always be a poor relative,'' analyst Yevgeny Volk
of the Heritage Foundation's Moscow office said. He added that
being invited to the summit isn't a recognition of Russian power,
''it's more of a courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin this week noted that Russia's early work with the G-7 was
focused on securing loans. That time has passed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, we abandon this format of communication,'' he declared.
He said he intends to use the summit to put forth Russia's views on
global issues, and Russian officials say security matters will be
high on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is concerned about terrorism brewing along its long and
porous Asian border. It also sees the U.S. proposal to build a
national missile-defense system as a significant security threat.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues will come together in Putin's visit July 19-20 to
North Korea, the first by a Russian leader to the isolated
Stalinist state. The United States cites North Korea as one of the
''rogue states'' whose suspected development of nuclear weapons
makes the missile-defense system necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Putin intends to raise the nuclear issue
during his Pyongyang visit, but the ITAR-Tass news agency quoted
Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Losyukov as saying that
military-technical cooperation could be discussed. Moscow could use
military aid to induce North Korea to back off on the nuclear
weapons issue.
</P>
<P>
   In light of North Korea's recent signs that it is tentatively
opening itself to the rest of the world, some commentators see
Putin's trip as an important demonstration of Russian diplomacy.
Moscow has already made it clear it wants to be a mediator between
North and South Korea, alongside Washington and Beijing, and now
Putin will be playing the role of intermediary between Pyongyang
and the West.
</P>
<P>
   ''Putin, with his visit to Pyongyang, is appearing at the
necessary time in the necessary place,'' commentator Dmitry Kosirev
wrote in the newspaper Nezavisimaya Gazeta.
</P>
<P>
   The Pyongyang visit will come on the heels of another stop that
is to sure to keep Putin's visibility high: Beijing. Tuesday's
summit will be Putin's first visit to China since he became
president.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan crafted a statement Saturday to be signed by
their presidents that condemns the proposed U.S. missile defense
system, Russian Embassy spokesman Vladimir Zakharov said in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more significantly, Putin and Chinese President
Jiang Zemin want to continue the close relations that have allowed
the former communist rivals to work against what they see as U.S.
global dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that the positions of such two great powers as
Russia and China, which are U.N. Security Council members and
possess nuclear weapons, should be taken into account by any
state,'' Itar-Tass quoted Ivanov as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the G-8 summit, Putin says, he will raise not only
international security issues, but push for further disarmament
measures and discuss environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers question how much influence Russia can wield,
given its troubled economy and its immense debts to foreign
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Delyagin, head of the Institute of Globalization
Problems, noted that Russia's share of the world economy is 0.6
percent, ''exactly 100 times less than that of the G-7.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is natural given such indicators that a question arises:
'How is it possible to take part in discussions as an equal?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
