<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hartford mayor wants chief to resign after evidence scandal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Mayor Mike Peters is calling for the
resignation of acting Police Chief Deborah Barrows amid revelations
her department has failed to comply with court orders to destroy
evidence seized during arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's not doing the job,'' Peters said, suggesting the city
may have to go outside the department for a leader until a
permanent chief is found. ''We cannot go on like this.''
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports about whether Barrows, who was
named acting chief when now-retired Chief Joseph Croughwell went on
medical leave 14 months ago, had agreed to step down. WVIT-TV
reported that she cleared her police office of personal belongings
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Barrows told The Hartford Courant Friday night that she had no
intention of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great city. I love living here and I'll continue to
do my job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Saundra Kee Borges, the person with the power to
remove Barrows, said she shared the mayor's frustration. She
planned to meet with Barrows on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The department came under fire a week ago when two state
agencies demanded hundreds of thousands of dollars they have been
owed them for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Money and property used as evidence is stored at the Hartford
Police Department's property room until the conclusion of a
criminal case. This year, Superior Court judges ordered the
department more than 700 times to destroy evidence, return personal
property to its rightful owners, or hand over property such as cash
or guns to other state agencies, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of these orders - including 80 percent of the
destruction orders -have not yet been obeyed, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Barrows issued a statement saying her department had
destroyed narcotics in nearly 4,000 cases since mid-1999. She also
said the department had handed over 601 guns since March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But that statement came just hours after the department handed
over 217 guns to the state police on Wednesday, by far the largest
single drop in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems that it goes from one extreme to another,'' said
Hartford Councilman Steven Harris, chairman of the council's public
safety committee. ''But now they are responding.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal surfaced when Chief State's Attorney John M. Bailey
reported that the department failed to share $380,000 intended for
its forfeiture account since April 1999. Twenty percent was
supposed to go to the state Department of Mental Health and
Addiction Services; 10 percent was to pay for salaries in Bailey's
office. The complaint was on the heels of demands by court
officials for the department to comply with their orders.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday and Thursday, the department turned over $118,601
to the state's attorney and about $4,500 to the Superior Court,
records show.
</P>
<P>
   A city audit of the property room, which started Wednesday, is
expected to be complete by Tuesday, Deputy City Manager James
Wright said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
