<DOCNO> APW20000715.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PRI Struggles With Opposition Area  </HEADLINE>
By MEGAN LARDNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEON, Mexico (AP) -- In the bustling city center, on the steps of
a cement-block building nearly hidden by taco stands and T-shirt
shops, seven members of the Institutional Revolutionary Party sit
silent and expressionless.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall, the painted image of President Ernesto Zedillo
grins, but no one smiles back. Surrounded on all sides by a city in
celebration after the historic victory of opposition presidential
candidate Vicente Fox, the drab PRI headquarters in Leon is a
lonely island.
</P>
<P>
   A city of 1 million people near the ranch where Fox grew up,
Leon is a stronghold of Fox's National Action Party, or PAN. It has
had a PAN mayor since 1988, and a PAN governor since 1991. When Fox
takes office on Dec. 1, Leon will have a PAN president too,
completing the humiliation of the party that has ruled Mexico since
1929.
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders here, more than anywhere else in Mexico, are getting
used to being in the opposition. Martin Ortiz says the most
important goal is not to lose the little presence the PRI maintains
in Leon. And he says if his party doesn't reorganize fast on the
national level, the PAN will become entirely dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important that what is happening in Leon doesn't occur on
a national level,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's support in Leon is overwhelming. His name appears on
stickers, billboards, car windshields and on the Fox boots
manufactured nearby. He held his last campaign rally here, setting
off an all-night party of honking horns and revelers in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, voters here elected a new PAN governor -- and Fox.
Fox's rival, PRI candidate Francisco Labastida, got only 20 percent
of the vote in Leon.
</P>
<P>
   At PRI headquarters, dejection hangs in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''He sold us out,'' says Vicente Flores, scowling at Zedillo's
image. He is angry that Zedillo recognized Fox's victory even
before the official results were announced.
</P>
<P>
   But Ortiz remains hopeful that one day the PRI will be strong
again.
</P>
<P>
   ''We aren't going to keep crying about the past,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
