<HEADLINE> Doctor facing death penalty in patient killings  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - At first glance, Dr. Michael Swango was
everything a patient could want in a physician: confident and
competent, with a good bedside manner.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors took a longer look and saw something else: they
charged the disgraced ex-doctor with fatally poisoning three
patients at a Long Island veterans hospital, part of a trail of
dead bodies going back 16 years and stretching from Ohio to
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything he did was designed to draw people in and make them
trust him,'' said U.S. Attorney Loretta Lynch, who announced
Swango's murder indictment. Now the man dubbed ''Dr. Death'' in a
tabloid headline faces the death penalty himself.
</P>
<P>
   Swango returns Monday to Long Island for his arraignment on the
murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   While authorities have only charged Swango with three murders,
the best-selling book ''Blind Eye: The Story of a Doctor who Got
Away with Murder'' suggested the death count could hit 35 patients
on two continents.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a charming, pathological liar,'' acknowledged Dr. Jordan
Cohen, dean of the Long Island medical school that ran the facility
where the alleged Swango slayings occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Swango's lies continued right up until 1997, when he was
arrested while boarding a plane for Saudi Arabia and another
medical job, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the 45-year-old Swango - just days from release at a
Colorado prison on unrelated charges - was accused of the 1993
murders of three patients at the Veterans Administration Hospital
in Northport.
</P>
<P>
   Swango allegedly injected the three with toxins. In two of the
cases, he then told other hospital staff that the patients'
families had issued ''do not resuscitate'' orders, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At first, he was a nice doctor,'' recalled Barron Harris Jr.,
whose father survived an alleged Swango attack on Long Island. ''I
remember shaking his hand - he said he would do the best he
could.''
</P>
<P>
   After the indictment last Tuesday, Swango's court-appointed
lawyer, Randi Chavis, did not return a call seeking comment.
Efforts to reach the lawyer later in the week also proved
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Swango's ''career'' began soon after his 1983 graduation from
the Southern Illinois University Medical School. There, according
to James B. Stewart's ''Blind Eye,'' the medical student was dubbed
''Double-0 Swango'' by classmates who joked that he had a license
to kill after several of his cases ended in death.
</P>
<P>
   While an intern at Ohio State University Hospital in 1984,
Swango allegedly killed a 19-year-old gymnast with a fatal dose of
potassium, according to the New York indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was never prosecuted for that crime, or for another
alleged poisoning of an OSU patient who survived.
</P>
<P>
   But Swango had another victim in Ohio: a teen driving the car
that initially injured the gymnast was convicted of reckless
homicide after her death. The youth spent 2&AMP;frac12; years on probation and
wound up with a record for a crime allegedly committed by Swango.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was not permitted to return for year two of his OSU
residency; he instead returned to his Quincy, Ill., home and took a
job as an emergency medical technician.
</P>
<P>
   His stint ended with his conviction for lacing his co-workers'
coffee and doughnuts with ant poison. Five of them became ill, and
Swango did two years of a five-year sentence behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   He also lost his medical license, which Swango apparently
considered a mere formality. His prison release coincided with
various unsuccessful attempts to revive his career, and he
eventually landed a 1993 residency at the State University of New
York at Stony Brook.
</P>
<P>
   Three Long Island patients - Thomas Sammarco, 73; George Siano,
60; and disabled Korean War veteran Aldo Serini - died between July
and October 1993 while staying at the veterans' hospital run by the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was cut loose by SUNY-Stony Brook after his past record
became public knowledge, and he soon relocated to Zimbabwe. Within
a year of his arrival, patients in a hospital there were showing
signs of poisoning, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1995, a Zimbabwe hospital suspended Swango from
practice. He was finally arrested two years later at O'Hare Airport
in Chicago, where he was boarding a flight to Saudi Arabia for a
new medical job.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago arrest was for lying about his criminal record on
his SUNY application. Prosecutors had, in part, brought those
charges to buy time in building a murder case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
