<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Iran Test Raises Concerns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Iran's reported test-firing of a medium-range
missile underscores long-standing concerns about the risk of
weapons proliferation in the Persian Gulf region, U.S. officials
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tehran television reported that Iran on Saturday fired the
Shahab-3 missile, which is capable of reaching Israel or U.S.
troops in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said Iran's effort to boost its missile
capabilities poses a serious threat to the area and undermines
nonproliferation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were ever to achieve an official dialogue with Iran,
this is certainly a subject we would want to discuss,'' said P.J.
Crowley, a spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''They (the Iranians) understand that in a dialogue we would
want to engage them on a number of issues, including the Middle
East peace process, their support of terrorism and their
development of weapons of mass destruction and the means to deliver
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said missile threats from
countries such as Iran and North Korea were behind development of a
proposed national anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley spoke in Thurmont, Md., where he is part of the group of
American officials supporting the Middle East peace conference at
Camp David sponsored by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said the United States would
continue its ''very extensive efforts to stop the proliferation of
missile technology and equipment to Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to place a high priority on this important missile
nonproliferation issue and to work closely with other like-minded
countries to stop the flow of sensitive missile items to Iran,''
the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
