<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scandal Rocks Brazilian Leader  </HEADLINE>
By PETER MUELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A new political scandal involving
top aides of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso has raised
questions about his ability to steer Brazil's budding economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption allegations have been leveled at Eduardo Jorge Caldas
Pereira, a former top presidential aide, and Planning and Budget
Minister Martus Tavares. While the government denies any
wrongdoing, the scandal keeps growing.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition congressmen are demanding a formal inquiry into the
links between Pereira and fugitive judge Nicolau dos Santos Neto,
convicted of embezzling nearly $100 million budgeted to build a
courthouse in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   In a published interview, Pereira admitted that Santos Neto
helped the government appoint labor court judges who would not
index wages to inflation, a key to the success of Cardoso's 1994
anti-inflation plan. But new allegations suggest their relationship
went a lot further.
</P>
<P>
   Santos Neto's phone records listed more than 100 calls to
Pereira. And an expose by IstoE newsmagazine indicated that Pereira
and Tavares were instrumental in approving millions of dollars in
extra funds for the judge's courthouse in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   IstoE's latest issue contains transcripts of phone conversations
the magazine said were taped by the federal police and the
Brazilian Intelligence Agency during a yearlong investigation of
Santos Neto. In one exchange, the judge boasts how impressed
Tavares was to learn that Pereira was his ''protector'' in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Tavares later issued a statement saying there was no reason to
deny the funds before 1998, when Brazil's General Accounting Office
reported irregularities with the courthouse construction. The extra
funds also were approved by the Congress, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the news took a toll on financial markets. After the
magazine hit newsstands Thursday, Brazil's benchmark Bovespa stock
index plunged 3.6 percent to finish at a two-week low, although it
rebounded Friday. Markets sustained the rise through closing.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso called an emergency Cabinet meeting Thursday night, but
the government denied reports that Tavares would resign.
</P>
<P>
   Although the magazine report also indicated that three senators
and one lower-chamber legislators helped to cover up the
overbilling, the big question was how the scandal would affect
Cardoso's effectiveness to lead the economy back to prosperity
after last year's recession.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no way this doesn't touch the president,'' said
political consultant Jose Luciano Dias of the think tank Goes e
Consultores in Brasilia, the capital. ''It will hurt him, but the
government still can quash it with relatively small damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Dias said the government coalition in Congress was strong enough
to block a panel of inquiry, and without a ''smoking gun'' the
scandal would tend to deflate.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a serious country it would be grounds for impeachment,''
said Dias. ''But this is Brazil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 1416 </TRAILER>
