<HEADLINE> Lazio filing shows almost $5 million raised  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio raised more than $4.96
million during the second quarter of this year as he geared up for
his U.S. Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton, aides said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Summary pages from a report prepared for filing with the Federal
Election Commission showed the Long Island Republican with almost
$6.2 million still in his campaign account. He spent almost $2.32
million during the three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio reported raising more than $4.4 million from individuals
and almost $551,000 from political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   Details of exactly where Lazio's money came from and what it was
spent on were to be made available on Monday when the congressman's
full FEC report is made public.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's summary pages were expected to be released
Sunday with her full FEC report made public on Monday, campaign
spokesman Howard Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of June, the Clinton campaign estimated it had raised
$5.1 million during the three-month period and said it expected to
report about $6.4 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   In those end-of-June projections, the Lazio campaign had
estimated its fund raising for the period at more than $4.5 million
and said it expected to have about $5.4 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very proud to have generated such incredible support in
such a short period of time,'' said Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal
Col on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio only entered the race on May 20 after Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani quit the contest in the face of prostate cancer and
marital problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
