<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State, local officials gear up for school construction funds  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The head of the agency charged with
overseeing New Jersey's largest public works project is heeding
advice from her father, a retired salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''He always said if competitors have good ideas, steal them,''
said Caren Franzini, executive director of the state Economic
Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
   So Franzini will be traveling around the country, learning how
other agencies handle such massive undertakings as New Jersey's
multibillion dollar school building program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill given final legislative approval last week, the
EDA will oversee the $8.6 billion state plan to rebuild and
renovate facilities in nearly all New Jersey's school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money, $6 billion, will be reserved for 30 poor
school districts that successfully sued the state for full funding
in the landmark Abbott vs. Burke lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   All those special needs school districts, plus about 50 more
that receive high levels of state aid, must go through the EDA for
their building projects, under the bill that awaits Gov. Christie
Whitman's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Other districts have the choice of having the state manage their
construction or doing it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So Franzini will be in charge of more than $6 billion worth of
construction in at least 80 districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The EDA is honored that the governor and the Legislature
thought well enough of us to do this,'' she said. ''We feel this a
challenge, and a wonderful opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Legislature has finally passed the bill following
two years of haggling, attention now turns to the EDA. The obscure
branch of state government was created in 1974 to boost the state's
economy by issuing bonds, making loans and offering technical
assistance to business start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The EDA is no stranger to building projects, having managed $1.3
billion worth of construction over the years. Some of its projects
include a technical center in North Brunswick, an office complex in
Trenton and the new Bergen County office building.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is different is, no one has ever had this magnitude of
construction,'' Franzini said, noting that the special needs
districts alone comprise 420 individual school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish its new responsibility, the EDA will be hiring
about 40 new staff members to operate a new division reserved for
school construction financing and management.
</P>
<P>
   One of its key tasks will be to keep the lines of communication
open among itself, school districts and the state Department of
Education, which will have final say on what kind of school
projects will be granted state aid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, David Sciarra, head of the Education Law Center, which
sued the state on behalf of the poor children, is worried that the
true needs of the poor schools will become lost in this new state
bureaucracy. He wants the Legislature to keep close tabs on how the
state responds to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a massive undertaking, and they have no track record.
There's going to be major problems,'' he said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra blames the state Department of Education for throwing
regulatory roadblocks in the path of the special needs schools. It
rejects major parts of their five-year facilities plans, sets vague
appeal timelines and writes flawed regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've been doing this for two or three years. We're tired of
this. It has to stop,'' he said. ''They would never treat suburban
districts like this.''
</P>
<P>
   John Crosbie, a Department of Education spokesman, denied
Sciarra's charges. The department will give the requests of special
needs districts a thorough and fair review, taking in account the
fact that tax money is at stake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As negotiations continue, people will see we're being prudent,
not unfair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reviewing all the special needs school district
plans, the department also must approve construction plans for any
of New Jersey's 616 school districts that apply for state said. So
like the EDA, it too must hire extra staff to assist with the extra
work, Crosbie said.
</P>
<P>
   The department will work with the EDA to ensure the construction
project goes smoothly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   School superintendents hope he's right
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Kohn, superintendent of Vineland schools, said his
district is desperate for the extra aid to address overcrowded
conditions. Local officials are going to Trenton this week, in
fact, to fine tune their facilities plans with the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We heartily welcome the infusion of much needed financial
resources to build the classrooms that have been lacking for many
years,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-15-00 1440 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
