<HEADLINE> Moderate Serbs May Be in Elections  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a sign of division in Kosovo Serb
ranks, Serb moderates said they might participate in the province's
first internationally supervised elections in Serbian areas where
NATO can provide security.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday had been the deadline for Kosovars of all groups --
Albanian, Serb, Turkish, Gypsies and others -- to register for
municipal elections in October.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. administrator Bernard Kouchner extended the deadline until
the close of business Wednesday to enable Serbs and others to
register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations needs substantial participation from all
ethnic groups to give legitimacy to the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement late Friday, Serbs in Gracanica, who are
associated with the Serbian Orthodox Church, said they would agree
to elections where ''there is a minimum of conditions that
municipal authorities actually function.'' Gracanica, a monastery
town, is about five miles south of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Serb
community in the small town of Leposavic in northern Kosovo was
also interested in registering.
</P>
<P>
   Serb leaders in Kosovska Mitrovica, however, remain opposed to
voting until the United Nations allows 1,500 Serbs to return this
month and draws up a firm timetable to allow another 210,000 to
come home.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials have resisted the demand. The outgoing Kosovo
chief of the U.N. refugee agency, Dennis McNamara, said a premature
return of Serbs would worsen the already tense ethnic climate in
the province.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Serbs fled the province when Yugoslav troops and
police withdrew in June 1999 after NATO's 78-day bombing of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs who stayed have been attacked by armed ethnic
Albanians seeking to drive the remaining 100,000 Serbs from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Dragisa Milovic, a Serb official in Kosovska Mitrovica, said:
''We have absolutely no security in Kosovo, nor are we able to move
around. Under those conditions, any election would be absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, a grenade was fired from an Albanian neighborhood
into the Serb sector of Kosovska Mitrovica. No injuries were
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The blast prompted rumors that a popular Serb cafe had been hit,
and angry Serbs flooded into the area. They dispersed early
Saturday when peacekeepers convinced them the cafe was not hit.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, another grenade was fired toward a complex of
three apartment buildings on the Serb side, exploding in an empty
apartment, NATO said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 1449 </TRAILER>
