<HEADLINE> Man pleads guilty in fatal crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) - A Freehold Township man faces 10 years
in prison after admitting he caused the accident that killed a New
York couple but spared their baby daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Tirpak, 26, pleaded guilty to two counts of vehicular
homicide and a single count of vehicular assault. He also admitted
driving while intoxicated, improper passing and reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
   He told Superior Court Judge Edward Turnbach on Friday that he
had been drinking shortly before the accident. His blood alcohol
content after the crash was 0.247, more than twice New Jersey's
legal limit of 0.10.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Tirpak's pickup truck was northbound on Route
537 last August when he went through a red light and broadsided a
car driven by Jhoni Rojas, of Long Island City, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas died four days later. His wife, Jeannie, died at the
scene. Their daughter, who was 1 at the time and in the back seat
with her mother, has since recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea agreement, Tirpak faces 10 years in prison when
he is sentenced Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Assistant Ocean County Prosecutor John Mercun said the
families of the victims were satisfied and felt justice had been
served.
</P>
</TEXT>
