<HEADLINE> Nurse vies for vacant Assembly seat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A nurse has jumped into the race for the
state Assembly seat vacated by Jerry Johnson, who was imprisoned in
April for burglarizing a female aide's home.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Saltzberg, 49, who lives in the Rochester suburb of
Pittsford, officially declared her Democratic candidacy Saturday
for the mainly rural 136th district, which extends across
Livingston, Monroe and Allegany counties in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Saltzberg said she's seeking political office for the first time
''for many of the same reasons I went into nursing in the first
place - I care about people and I know I can make a difference in
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Texas, Saltzberg moved to Rochester in 1977 and has
been a registered nurse for 29 years. She has lobbied in Albany for
nursing-related organizations, served on the faculty at the
University of Rochester and is studying for a doctorate in
education.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are backing Joseph Errigo of Conesus, a retired
court reporter and a county commissioner on the Rochester-Genesee
Regional Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a Republican, agreed to a felony plea deal that ended
his 28-year political career and put him in jail for up to 12
months. He was elected to the first of four terms in the state
Assembly in 1992 and had been up for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   By failing to resign his seat by April 1, his successor will not
be selected until the November election.
</P>
