<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Psst: Wanna buy a steam locomotive?  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEARNY, N.J. (AP) - Psst: Wanna buy a steam locomotive?
</P>
<P>
   For anywhere from $1 million to $3 million, you can buy the
Chesapeake &AMP; Ohio No. 614, the last steam passenger locomotive
built in the United States. The owner will even throw in two
auxiliary cars for free.
</P>
<P>
   Rail buffs, train lovers and Lionel fans: stick THIS under your
kid's Christmas tree. It's an 890,000-pound, 112-foot long, fully
functional steam locomotive that can reach speeds of 125 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The train, which made tourist runs on NJ Transit tracks between
Port Jervis, N.Y., and Hoboken in the 1990s, is being sold because
its owner recently moved to Canada and plans a new tourist railroad
with bridges that can't support the weight of old No. 614.
</P>
<P>
   With such a hefty price tag, the average rail buff won't be able
to afford it; so far, it's been offered to Microsoft founder Bill
Gates, Wall Street whiz Warren Buffett, and actor Kevin Costner -
all acknowledged train fanciers - but they haven't bitten.
</P>
<P>
   An auction Saturday at NJ Transit Meadows Maintenance Facility
drew a high bid of only $200,000, well below what owner Ross
Rowland Jr. says it's worth. An auctioneer will work next week with
others who expressed interest in the train to see if an acceptable
bid can be negotiated, Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the last mainline steam engine built in North America
in 1948, as railroads were transitioning from steam to diesel,''
said Rowland, who has owned No. 614 since 1979, when he bought it
from the CSX railroad. ''It's been thoroughly refurbished and
updated, and it's the only steam locomotive in North America that
has all the equipment and appliances you'd need to pull an Amtrak
train.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is the only steam engine ever leased by Amtrak,
having pulled ''The Cardinal'' through West Virginia at speeds
approaching 80 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The locomotive has a proud history in American railroading. When
it rolled out of the Lima Locomotive Works in Ohio in January 1948,
it pulled the Chesapeake &AMP; Ohio Railroad's premier express
passenger trains, ''The George Washington'' and ''The Fast Flying
Virginian'' between Richmond, Va. and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It was retired from service in 1952 and relegated to a storage
roundhouse in Kentucky for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, it was underwent a facelift and was donated to the
Baltimore &AMP; Ohio Railroad Museum in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   When Rowland bought it, he oversaw a crew of 15 mechanics and
more than 100 volunteers who completely rebuilt the locomotive,
which generates power by burning coal and dumping water on the
embers to generate steam to power its giant pistons that turn the
wheels. It took 18 months and $1.5 million to bring No. 614 up to
snuff; it can now pull a 25-car passenger train all day without
having to stop for service.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland most recently used it for ''Iron Horse Rambles'' along
NJ Transit's Port Jervis tracks; nearly 17,000 people, some from as
far away as Australia, New Zealand and Japan, have paid for the
chance to ride behind the restored steam engine.
</P>
<P>
   He's starting up a new tourist railroad in Victoria, British
Columbia, but can't use the black and silver behemoth on those
tracks. Bridges in the area can handle about 200 tons, Rowland
said; No. 614 weighs more than twice that.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has been a train nut ever since he was a kid. Yes, he
said, he had a set of Lionel toy trains when he was 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I quickly grew tired of those, and wanted the big ones,
the real ones,'' he said. ''I've been in love with trains ever
since I was a kid; I still am today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Anderson of Yonkers, N.Y. works for the New York City
Transit Authority, maintaining trains. He stopped by the auction
just to take a peek at some living history.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the last of its type,'' he said as a light rain vaporized
on the heated locomotive Saturday morning. ''I've seen it go on a
lot of excursions, and I just wanted to see it one last time.''
</P>
<P>
   The romance of the steam engine era is a main motivation for
collectors like Rowland who buy and lovingly maintain the old
trains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Walt Disney, who was a huge rail buff, said it best: 'With a
steam engine, it's a happening; with a diesel, it's another
train,''' Rowland said. ''Every kid in school learns about the
importance of the steam engine in the development of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without the steam engine, there would have been no westward
expansion,'' he said. ''It enabled the industrial revolution and
the population of the western two-thirds of the United States.
Combine that with the sights and sounds of a steam engine as it
passes by you - the hiss of the steam, the sound of the whistle,
the way the ground shakes underneath you - and it's almost an alive
machine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
