<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citing neglect, state shuts home for elderly in Montvale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONTVALE, N.J. (AP) - Nine unwashed, underfed tenants led state
investigators to shut down a Montvale boarding home for the elderly
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of the Hillas Vale Guest Lodge, between the ages
of 70 and 90, were glad to leave, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were living without supervision, 80-year-old people
cleaning their own clothes and cooking their own food, and some of
them paid $1,000 a month to live there,'' said Victor Baykal, chief
of the state Bureau of Rooming and Boarding House Standards.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the home, Maureen Culhane, faces no further
disciplinary action beyond its closing.
</P>
<P>
   The nine seniors did not have any serious health problems,
although all were noticeably thin, said Jay Meyerowitz, medical
director for the Potomac Group homes, where the state temporarily
moved the residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Emotionally, they were very distraught and very distressed,''
he said. ''They were slightly disheveled. I would say unkempt. They
looked like they hadn't been provided baths or clean clothes for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents told officials they had been left with nothing to eat
but spaghetti sauce for one three-day stretch.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators had tried twice before to shut down the
home, but each time they returned, they found better supervision
than when they had initially visited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
