<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Cop's cop' Sardino, former Syracuse police chief, dies  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Former Syracuse Police Chief Thomas J.
Sardino, who began his career raiding gambling joints alone on his
off-hours then pioneered community policing, is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The tough, compassionate cop died Friday of heart failure at 72.
</P>
<P>
   Sardino was respected statewide and nationally. His innovative
approach included pioneering work in community policing, the
program that puts more officers walking and touring the streets and
talking to residents to try to head-off crime before it happens. He
also started the city's first neighborhood watch program in the
city back in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The chief with a master's degree in business administration from
Syracuse University left the Syracuse police force after 15 years
as chief in 1985. He then moved to Upper Marlboro, Md., to lead the
Amtrak federal police force until he suffered a stroke in 1994 and
returned to central New York.
</P>
<P>
   He is a former president of the New York State Association of
Chiefs of Police and of the International Association of Chiefs of
Police.
</P>
<P>
   Sardino joined the police department after two years in the Army
during the Korean War and rose through the ranks with extraordinary
speed. He made sergeant after five years, lieutenant after another
five years, and captain five years later, after scoring the highest
mark on record for the state on the civil service exam.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s newspapers called Sardino a one-man vice
squad. Alone on the streets, he spent off-duty hours raiding
illegal gambling enterprises. He wanted to send a message that the
police department was not going to be lax in going after gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to become the city's longest-sitting police chief,
the author of four books on policing that were studied in police
academies across the country and in foreign nations, and head of a
worldwide association of police chiefs. He was the calming
influence in volatile demonstrations at Syracuse University and at
riots on city streets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tom's life revolved around the city of Syracuse and the police
department,'' said his wife, Nina Sardino, who would occasionally
ride along with him on patrol. ''He was a lucky person. He had a
job that he absolutely loved.''
</P>
<P>
   A sharp-dresser, Sardino's craggy face and his trademark cigar
were fixtures at city crime scenes for nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his fairness as well as his toughness, Sardino was a
nationally recognized police chief until then Mayor-elect Tom Young
replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Sardino name is synonymous with law enforcement,''
Syracuse Mayor Roy Bernardi said Friday. ''Tom Sardino epitomized
what law enforcement is about. He was tough on crime but could step
back and see the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernardi ordered city flags flown at half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   Sardino's reputation was built in part for his actions in 1970,
when Syracuse University was home to protests of the Vietnam war.
Some protesters sought to take the marches to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Sardino arrives, chomping his cigar. Students are yelling.
Sardino takes control.
</P>
<P>
   There's no riot, no tear gas, no fires, no bottle throwing.
Instead, Sardino gives students the go-ahead for their march, on
two conditions. The march must be orderly, and Sardino must lead
it.
</P>
<P>
   That calm in the face of disorder was repeated at Syracuse
University 15 years later during an anti-apartheid protest. The
school demanded students remove their shacks and banners, but
Sardino said he wouldn't step in.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got the right to demonstrate, and we're going to
protect that right as long as it's peaceful and nonviolent,'' he
told the cheering students.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, former Lt. George Georgiadi accused then Mayor Lee
Alexander and Sardino, who once considered running for mayor, of
asking him to perform dirty tricks for them during the 1977 mayoral
race. An Onondaga County grand jury issued no indictments in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a remarkable guy,'' Georgiadi said Friday. ''You got to
give the devil his due. Probably one of the greatest cops there
ever was in Syracuse. He was honest, dedicated, didn't play games,
didn't pull punches. In my mind, he just got political.''
</P>
<P>
   Sardino once offered himself as a lightning rod during a
neighborhood riot that broke out on Labor Day one year, said
Richard Haumann, Sardino's friend and deputy chief for several
years. About 100 people were battling on a city street with fists,
rocks and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   ''He went into the middle of the street so that he became the
target,'' said Haumann, who accompanied his mentor. Sardino stood
his ground as he was pelted with rocks. ''He got hurt. We both got
hurt,'' Haumann said. ''He had no fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Frank Halse, who was the Methodist chaplain at Syracuse
University, said the protests reached a boiling point on the day of
the Kent State shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The students were on a tear at the campus and had lighted oxygen
bottles that were strewn all over the construction site for a new
geology building. Sardino showed up the next morning with trucks to
get the oxygen bottles to avoid injuries. In a steady, calm voice,
Sardino negotiated with the protesters and stood by while the
bottles were taken out.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the time he was doing this, there was a kid pounding on
him, calling him every four-letter word in the world,'' Halse said.
''And (Sardino) never turned a hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Sardino thanked the protesters, then put his arm around the kid
who was screaming at him.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're all right, kid,'' Sardino told him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kid broke down in tears and fell into (Sardino's) chest,
and he just held him and let the kid cry it out,'' Halse said. ''It
was beautiful. To me, it was the essence of the man's character on
display.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Nina, five children and eleven
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral with full honors is planned for Monday at the
Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception in Syracuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-15-00 1606 </TRAILER>
