<DOCNO> APW20000715.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect in assault on police officer rejects plea deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The man suspected of seriously injuring a
Rochester police officer has rejected a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Jones, who is accused of hitting Officer Scott McLaughlin
with a car while suffering an epileptic seizure, said he would
rather risk a stiffer sentence after a trial than accept a prison
term of 10 years for first-degree assault.
</P>
<P>
   Although he faces up to 25 years behind bars if he's convicted,
Jones is adamant that he didn't intend to cause McLaughlin's
life-threatening brain injuries, said his minister, the Rev. Wilson
Dicker of Northside Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no evil intent,'' Dicker told the Rochester Democrat
and Chronicle. ''He had a seizure. There's nothing in the law
against having a seizure. But he's sorry it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Howard R. Relin said Jones isn't charged with
intentionally injuring McLaughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 42, is charged with acting with depraved indifference to
human life for failing to take prescribed anti-seizure medication
and driving without a license after a physician warned him against
getting behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, 36, was injured Jan. 16 as he stood on a sidewalk. A
car allegedly driven by Jones jumped the curb and hit McLaughlin,
causing injuries that put McLaughlin in a coma for three weeks.
McLaughlin, who was released from a hospital June 14 and is
recovering well, consented to a plea-bargain that would have given
Jones the minimum prison time allowed for first-degree assault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
