<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pipeline Extinguished in Nigeria  </HEADLINE>
By AMBA DADSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADEJE, Nigeria (AP) -- Five days after a pipeline blast killed
200 in southern Nigeria, a blaze caused by the explosion died out
Saturday and villagers were slowly returning to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline near the villages of Adeje and Oviri-Court, north
of the oil port of Warri, still gushed fuel but the fire that had
been burning for days fizzled. Twisted bicycles and metal wash
basins remained near a few burned and decaying bodies that had yet
to be collected.
</P>
<P>
   A state petroleum company spokesman warned that pipeline
vandalism across this oil-rich country was increasing despite the
risk posed to perpetrators of sparking yet another explosion or
being arrested or shot by police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vandalism of our pipelines resulting in frequent fires
constitute a serious national security problem,'' Ndu Ughamadu
said. ''There is an urgent need for the federal government to deal
with the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's blast some of the residents in nearby villages
went into hiding out of fear they would be blamed for the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cause of the blast remains unclear, the pipe had
been punctured by vandals who syphoned off the fuel to sell on the
black market.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, which carries fuel from a refinery in Warri to
northern Nigeria, had been vandalized in the same spot seven times
since January, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those killed in the blast were poor villagers, including
many children, who were scooping up the fuel with pots and cans.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the blaze, vandals have punctured the pipeline
again, hoping to salvage remaining fuel, an Adeje village resident,
who asked not to be named, said Saturday. The claim could not be
independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the toll from the explosion jumped to 200, pushed up
by the discovery of more bodies and the deaths of badly burned
villagers.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll could rise higher still, although exact figures
may never be known. Many of the injured -- including those with
serious burns -- remain in hiding and some of the bodies were
hastily disposed of by villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross official Wilfred Emovon said authorities were slowly
trying to piece together the scale of the disaster but said
villagers were being uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is going to take months before we actually know (how many
were killed and injured). People came from different areas, even
different states,'' Emovon said.
</P>
<P>
   One Adeje resident, a young man who identified himself only as
Moses, worried another disaster was possible because some people
remained determined to collect fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of these boys are so stubborn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state petroleum company has blamed organized crime networks
for encouraging pipeline vandalism and using violence against
security guards and police who try to stop the vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is the world's sixth-largest oil exporter, accounting
for about one-twelfth of oil imported by the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 1641 </TRAILER>
