<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Promises on Land Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HARTNACK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- The leader of a war veterans group said
Saturday that his followers would stay put until he was satisfied
that the government's land redistribution plan was working, defying
an order that his group leave the 1,700 farms they have occupied
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Chenjerai Hunzvi, leader of a group that has spearheaded
occupations of more than 1,600 white-owned farms, made the remarks
shortly after Zimbabwe's Vice President Joseph Msika promised to
hand over 200 formerly white-owned farms to peasants on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Hunzvi's supporters were on the 200
farms. The often violent farm invasions have left four white
farmers and at least three farm workers dead.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions mounted as police erected roadblocks on all main roads
leading to Harare and Chengetai Zvauya, a reporter with the
independently owned Sunday Standard, was badly beaten at the war
veterans' meeting after a woman accused him of working for a paper
that did not support them. A newspaper spokesman said Zvauya was
treated for his injuries and filed a police report.
</P>
<P>
   The Commercial Farmers Union, which represents many of the white
farmers, also reported an increase in death threats and attempts to
drive farmers off of their land. The union said it had been told it
would receive a list of farms the government plans to redistribute
on Monday, and that occupiers should start leaving farms ''almost
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Msika said Saturday that the government did not expect any
resistance and that war veterans and others were being taken from
some of the 1,700 farms they have occupied and moved to the newly
nationalized land.
</P>
<P>
   Hunzvi, however, said he and his supporters would remain on the
land but allow the government two weeks to declare all occupied
farms state property. He did not specify what he would do if the
government disregarded his instructions.
</P>
<P>
   The government in late May listed more than 800 farms it plans
to seize and redistribute to landless blacks, but owners of about
600 of the farms have launched legal appeals against the
government's proposals. The government says the appeals will likely
be denied.
</P>
<P>
   War veterans and ruling party militants began occupying
white-owned farms in February, after President Robert Mugabe lost a
constitutional referendum that would have empowered him to
nationalize the farms without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party has since passed a law allowing government to
do so anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Henwood, president of the Commercial Farmers Union, said as
long as things are done within the framework of the law, the
redistribution should go smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once farmers know what the situation is, and it has settled
down, then farmers will be much happier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Msika said compensation for the farmers still depended on
''Britain, the former colonial ruler, which created this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain pledged millions of dollars for land reform at
independence and delivered nearly 90 percent of that money before
freezing the fund in 1990, saying Zimbabwe violated the agreement
by forcing unwilling farmers to sell to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is facing its worst economic crisis since independence,
and the land crisis has crippled the crucial agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party won a narrow victory in the June 24-25
parliamentary elections. The main opposition party, the Movement
for Democratic Change, won 57 of 120 contested seats. The previous
parliament had only three opposition delegates.
</P>
<P>
   White farmers currently control about 70 percent of the
country's commercial farmland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 1702 </TRAILER>
