<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reports: 13 More Killed in Algeria  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Ongoing violence in Algeria has left 13
people, including a family of four, dead over the past several
days, national newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a peace drive by President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, Islamic
insurgents continue to carry out daily attacks in this North
African nation. Violence broke out 1992, when the army canceled
legislative elections the now-outlawed Islamic Salvation Front was
set to win.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people have been killed in the eight years of
fighting since then.
</P>
<P>
   Attackers killed a family of four Friday in their home in Oran,
600 kilometers (370 miles) west of Algiers, the daily El Watan
reported. Neighbors discovered the mutilated bodies of the victims,
whose throats had been slit, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, assailants opened fire on a police patrol that was
passing near Zemmouri, 60 kilometers (37 miles) east of the
capital, killing two officers and wounding another, Liberte daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Another attack this week in the eastern town of Taglait left a
City Hall employee dead, Liberte said.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers also reported that security forces killed six alleged
Islamic militants in two separate crackdowns on Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The army has been hunting down militants since a January
deadline for insurgents to turn in their weapons in exchange for
partial amnesty, an offer that applied to those who had not
committed rape, murder or bombings.
</P>
<P>
   (str-ad)
</P>
</TEXT>
