<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Evasion Filed Against Sharif  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTOCK FORT, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan's military government
filed another tax evasion case against deposed Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif on Saturday, accusing him of failing to declare the income
to buy property worth millions of dollars, court officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's father, Mian Mohammed Sharif and his mother, Shamim
Akther, have also been charged with tax evasion in connection with
the same land purchase. The charges were laid by Pakistan's
National Accountability Bureau, which is investigating corruption
cases against scores of the country's most powerful people,
including politicians and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   The special accountability court hearing Sharif's corruption and
tax evasion cases has been set up in the 16th century Attock Fort,
60 miles east of the capital Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Attock Fort on Saturday, former southern Sindh
provincial minister Farooq Sattar was found guilty of corruption
and sentenced to 14 years in jail. He is expected to appeal. He
also was fined $900,000 and disqualified from holding public office
for 21 years, the maximum penalty under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif is currently serving two concurrent life terms on charges
of terrorism and hijacking. He is appealing the convictions and
sentence. He also faces corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's wife, Kulsoom, has fiercely defended her husband's
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is another cooked up case filed by the military rulers
against our family,'' Mrs. Sharif said in a telephone interview.
''We will pass through these trying times with our heads held
high.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest tax evasion charge, Sharif bought and
developed a 450-acre estate in Raiwind, 15 miles west of Lahore.
The project was valued at $4.6 million, but Sharif did not declare
that money and the estate was purchased in Sharif's mother's name.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum sentence if found guilty is 14 years in jail. Sharif
also would be disqualified from holding a public office.
</P>
<P>
   Army chief Gen. Pervez Musharraf overthrew Sharif's civilian
government in a bloodless coup on Oct. 12, accusing Sharif of
massive corruption, undermining the constitution and destroying
institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
