<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB: Mechanical problem, medication caused Newark plane crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Federal investigators have concluded that
mechanical trouble, coupled with the pilot's use of a painkiller,
caused a plane crash that killed four people last November.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board's final report on the
Nov. 26 crash closely mirrored preliminary results issued in June:
that the pilot, Itzhak Jacoby, was taking fiorinal, a barbituate
known to cause drowsiness and dizziness. Jacoby had a history of
migraine headaches and was using the painkiller for them.
</P>
<P>
   The final report also found evidence that two of the small
plane's three gyroscopes weren't functioning properly. The spinning
devices are crucial to enabling a pilot to determine if a plane is
flying level.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby, his wife, Gail, and their 13-year-old daughter, Atira,
all from Maryland, died in the crash. A man injured on the ground,
Alfred Walker, of Newark, died eight weeks after the crash from
injuries he sustained in it.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby, 56, had reported gyroscope problems on the Beechcraft
Bonanza S35 before crashing.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said failed gyroscopes could have doomed the flight that
crashed into a factory and barreled down a street, shedding its
wings and tail before hitting a Kentucky Fried Chicken restaurant.
Twenty-five people were injured on the ground; the plane caused
more than $1 million in property damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
