<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelby Lynne Returns With New Sound  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- In 1991, Shelby Lynne was supposed to be the
next big thing in country music. By the time she was 22, she had
recorded a duet with George Jones and won a top country music
award.
</P>
<P>
   But formula-fitting country music didn't suit Lynne, who earned
a reputation for being talented but temperamental. And after five
albums she abandoned Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's back with her own sound, derived from her roots in
south Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ''I make music for myself, because I am the listener and I want
to hear what I like,'' said Lynne, now 31. ''It's not fluffy, it's
real. I want something that moves me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne recorded the duet ''If I Could Bottle This Up'' with
George Jones in 1998. She won the Academy of Country Music's
Horizon Award for Best New Female Artist in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I'd play music, even if it was just in the Holiday Inn.
I am music. I have to play music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 1743 </TRAILER>
