<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Barak, Arafat Meet
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat engaged with their delegations in informal
talks at the Mideast summit today as some delegates toured the Gettysburg
battlefield. ''The teams continued to meet informally and at times that involved
the leaders,'' said a White House spokesman who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. Unlike last night, there was no three-way meeting between the
leaders, he said. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was also involved in the
latest round of activity and a more formal meeting was planned for this evening.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iran Tests Ballistic Missile
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran test-fired the Shahab-3 missile Saturday, Tehran
television reported, the second trial in two years for the medium-range weapon
capable of reaching Israel or U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia. The state broadcast
said the test was in line with Iran's ''policy of strengthening its defense
capability on the basis of the principle of deterrence.'' In Israel, Deputy
Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh expressed concern Saturday about the missile test
''because Iran actively and relentlessly undermines the peace process through
various terrorist organizations.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Peacekeepers Freed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. officials said Saturday that in a rare
display of force, U.N. troops freed all 222 peacekeepers and 11 military
observers trapped by rebels inside a U.N. base in eastern Sierra Leone. The U.N.
observers, of various nationalities, were flown safely by British military
helicopters to Freetown. The 222 Indian troops, who had been unable to leave
their base in the rebel headquarters of Kailahun since May, meanwhile faced
heavy rebel gunfire as they made their way by road toward the U.N.-controlled
town of Daru, U.N. spokesman Nigerian Lt. Commander Patrick Coker said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Russian Army Train Bombed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- A woman was killed and six servicemen were wounded
Saturday when an explosion ripped through a Russian military train in the
restive republic of Chechnya, a news report said. NTV commercial television said
that the train's locomotive was hauling two carloads of soldiers toward Russian
headquarters in Khankala, a suburb of the capital Grozny. The blast occurred
near the town of Dzhalka, killing a cook and injuring six of the men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Immunity Helped Turn Waco Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- Long before an advisory jury decided the federal
government was not responsible for the deaths of Branch Davidians in the Waco
siege, U.S. attorneys had turned the case in their favor. By invoking a federal
law known as the discretionary function exemption, they eliminated several
allegations in the $675 million wrongful death lawsuit brought by survivors of
the 1993 siege and relatives of those who died. That exemption gives federal
officials room to make judgment calls and carry them out without fear of being
sued, even if their decisions prove to be bad.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pipeline Extinguished in Nigeria
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ADEJE, Nigeria (AP) -- Five days after a pipeline blast killed 200 in
southern Nigeria, a blaze caused by the explosion died out Saturday and
villagers were slowly returning to their homes. The pipeline near the villages
of Adeje and Oviri-Court, north of the oil port of Warri, still gushed fuel but
the fire that had been burning for days fizzled. Twisted bicycles and metal wash
basins remained near a few burned and decaying bodies that had yet to be
collected.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Source: Saudis Pumping More Oil
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Saudi Arabia has started pumping the
extra oil it had promised earlier this month in an effort to ease fuel prices,
an official from an OPEC country said Saturday. Saudi Arabia's national oil
company Aramco raised production this week, according to the official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity. He did not say how much more oil the kingdom was
pumping, but the Saudis said early this month they would increase oil output by
500,000 barrels a day. Oil traders in Asia confirmed they had been told to
expect more Saudi oil in August.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Everett Ejected in Red Sox 6-4 Win
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Boston's Carl Everett head-butted umpire Ron Kulpa in a heated
argument after being ejected, and replacement Brian Daubach hit a three-run
homer that led the Red Sox over the New York Mets 6-4 today. Kulpa tossed
Everett as they argued about whether the Red Sox star was standing too close to
the plate. The plate umpire then drew a proper boundary with his foot and the
argument quickly escalated. Everett bumped the umpire twice and head-butted him,
and had to be restrained.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
