<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Barak, Arafat Meet  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat engaged with their
delegations in informal talks at the Mideast summit Saturday as
some delegates toured the Gettysburg battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ''The teams continued to meet informally and at times that
involved the leaders,'' said a White House spokesman who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a meeting Friday night, there was no three-way meeting
between the leaders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was also involved in the
latest round of activity and a more formal meeting was planned
Saturday evening after the close of the Jewish sabbath, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 members of the Israeli and Palestinian delegations took
advantage of a standing offer and toured the battlefield near
Gettysburg, site of the July 1863 bloody engagement generally
considered the Civil War's turning point.
</P>
<P>
   The three leaders met together for just the second time Friday
night following a dinner in a rustic Camp David cabin.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute session, which ended early Saturday, was disclosed
later in the morning by the White House. The three leaders had met
when the summit opened on Tuesday. Since then, Clinton has shuttled
between the two sides in talks described as contentious and
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders were joined only by interpreters and note-takers.
Earlier, Barak was the host at a Sabbath dinner attended by
delegation members.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the Jewish day of rest, negotiators kept to a slower
pace Saturday. The Sabbath lasts from sundown Friday until sundown
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the original Camp David summit in 1978, when President Jimmy
Carter guided Israel and Egypt to a peace breakthrough, then-Prime
Minister Menachem Begin solicited a rabbinical opinion that still
holds today: It is permissible for Israeli delegates to talk peace
on the Sabbath if it does not involve work such as note-taking or
use of mechanical devices such as the golf carts that are the
preferred way to get around.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met Saturday morning with his own negotiating team at
the presidential retreat in Maryland's Catoctin mountains 90 miles
northwest of Washington. There was no immediate word on other talks
taking place during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Participants have agreed to disclose nothing of the substance of
the negotiations, but U.S. officials briefing reporters have
repeatedly used words like ''grappling'' and ''struggling'' to
characterize the atmosphere. At one point, White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart described the issues as ''intractable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are deeply divided on key questions including the
boundaries of any future Palestinian state, the fate of several
million Palestinian refugees and status of Jerusalem, which both
sides claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   While the negotiators went about their task, Palestinian
demonstrators took to the streets in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
urging Arafat to stand firm. Israeli peace activists also gathered
in the Jerusalem suburb of Abu Dis to urge that Palestinians be
given a foothold in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Palestinian demonstrators made thinly veiled threats
of violence should the summit fail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We give all our support to Arafat and the negotiators in Camp
David,'' said Shafik Tluly, a member of the leadership of Arafat's
Fatah faction. ''But if the summit fails, we are ready for all
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Gaza Strip, Sheik Ahmed Yassin, spiritual leader of the
radical Shiite Muslim group Hamas, told followers that the Camp
David talks were ''a conspiracy to put pressure on Palestinians to
give up their natural rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamas opposes any peace with Israel and has staged dozens of
attacks including suicide bombings to try to halt the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the summit is still uncertain. Clinton is
scheduled to travel to Japan on Wednesday, but U.S. officials have
said that should not be considered a deadline for wrapping up the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Palestinian Authority: http://www.pna.org/mininfo/
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs:
http://www.israel-mfa.gov.il/mfa/home.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
