<DOCNO> APW20000715.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small group commemorate 10 airmen killed in bomber crash 56 years ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN, N.H. (AP) - Fifty-six years after 10 airmen died when
their B-17 bomber crashed into a Maine mountain, a small group of
New Hampshire residents did something no one else ever bothered to
do: they commemorated the site.
</P>
<P>
   The men from Berlin, Gorham and Errol gather Saturday near the
hamlet of Wilson's Mills in the unincorporated Maine township of
Cupsuptic and dedicated a 600-pound granite monument.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard about the crash years ago from an old logger,'' Mike
Rozek of Berlin told columnist John Clayton of The Union Leader of
Manchester. ''I figured if nobody else was going to do anything,
then I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Rozek had no ties to any of the men killed in the crash. But he
was touched by the fact nothing had ever been done to mark the site
and commemorate the airmen's sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, it was just a real sad state of affairs. I know that
life goes on and everyone's too busy to stop. Well, I stopped,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rozek first asked Donald Piper, owner of Nicoletti Memorials in
Berlin, about creating a permanent monument at the crash site.
Piper quickly offered to donate a 600-pound granite slab.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no idea about the history or the tragedy until Mike
brought it to light for me,'' Piper said. ''He felt strongly there
should be something there to identify what happened at that
location and I agreed. The only reason I got interested was because
of his enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   At the request of northern New Hampshire historian Richard
Pinette request, the owners of the land, the Mead Corp., gave
permission for the monument to be installed.
</P>
<P>
   Lucien Dupuis, commander of VFW Post 2520 in Berlin, volunteered
an honor guard for the ceremony and Lionel Roy agreed to sing at
the dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Pinette also wrote to Secretary of Defense William Cohen seeking
financial support. But that request was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Berlin-Gorham Rotary Club instead donated money
to pay for engraving the names of the 10 airmen onto the monument,
along with the following words:
</P>
<P>
   This W.W. II Memorial is dedicated to the crew of B-17G
43-38023, which crashed here on July 11, 1944. They gave their
lives for their country.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 were: 2nd Lt. John T. Cast, pilot, Springfield, Ohio; 2nd
Lt. John W. Drake, co-pilot, Port Arthur, Texas; 2nd Lt. William H.
Hudgens, navigator, Flagstaff, Ariz.; 2nd Lt. Robert S. Talley,
bombardier, San Angelo, Texas; S/Sgt. Wayne D. McCavran, engineer,
Seymour, Iowa; Sgt. Cecil Murphy, radio operator, Fall City, Neb.;
Sgt. Clarence M. Wain, gunner, Ten Sleep, Wyo.; Sgt. Gerald V.
Biddle, gunner, East Orange, N.J.; Sgt. James A. Benson,
armorer-gunner, Clark, S.D.; Cpl. John H. Jones Jr. gunner,
Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The bomber had left Kearney, Neb., bound for England by way of
Bangor, Maine. As it flew over New Hampshire, Murphy made radio
contact with Grenier Field in Manchester at 10:55 a.m. That was the
last anyone heard from the bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it was learned the plane had slammed into a ridge near
the top of Deer Mountain in the remote Maine wilderness at 200
miles per hour. There were no survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The largest piece of the plane found was a 3&AMP;frac12;-foot section of
wing. Salvage teams recovered so little that in time, the military
ordered in a bulldozer, and after removing the live ammunition, the
shards of the once-mammoth fuselage were simply plowed under.
</P>
<P>
   Rozek, 44, born 12 years after the crash, learned of it one day
during a conversation with a man who once logged in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to know more,'' Rozek said.
</P>
<P>
   Rozek thought about it for years, all the time trying to find
out more details. Then in 1995, thousands of military documents
were declassified, and he got his hands on the official report
filed July 22, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   While the body of the co-pilot, Drake, was officially
identified, other remains were hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rozek decided something had to be done after talking to Don
Glover, who lives in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me one day a cousin of one of the men who died went to
the site,'' Rozek said. ''As far as he was concerned, that's where
his cousin is buried and he was devastated that there was nothing
to mark it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-15-00 1819 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
