<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Queens mom gets 25 years to life for murdering her 5-year-old daughter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Queens woman, convicted of murdering her
5-year-old daughter, has been sentenced to 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   ''You didn't extend any mercy to her, and you don't deserve any
mercy from me,'' said state Supreme Court Justice Richard Buchter
in sentencing Eva Campos on Friday. Campos was convicted last month
of second-degree murder in the July 25, 1998, death of Rosario
Ladino.
</P>
<P>
   Campos confessed to police that she repeatedly hit the 38-pound
girl because the child had soiled her underwear that morning,
according to trial testimony. She pummeled Rosario with a shoe so
many times that she lost count. Campos then sat by, as the girl
slowly died, having seizures, foaming at the mouth and bleeding
from her ears.
</P>
<P>
   ''At that point one would have to have a heart of stone not to
at least try to help this poor battered child,'' Buchter said.
Campos did not call 911, even after the child died in her bed that
afternoon, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Frank DeGaetano told the court that
an autopsy revealed more than 120 distinct injuries on the girl's
body.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario's father, Laurentino Ladino, pleaded guilty in March
1999 to manslaughter and endangering the welfare of a child. The
manslaughter charge was dropped last month in exchange for his
cooperation with the Queens district attorney's office, and he was
sentenced to time served.
</P>
<P>
   He was not called to testify at Campos' trial because he was not
present when the fatal beating took place, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's two other children, an 8-year-old boy and a
toddler, are now in foster care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
