<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspected thief strong-armed by determined victim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - The strong arm of the lady teamed up with
the long arm of the law to collar a man suspected in several
drive-by robberies.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end of Brian J. Hawley's suspected two-week
crime spree came around 5 p.m. Thursday when he tried to grab a
woman's purse in a supermarket parking lot. Police said he parked
his van right up against the woman's car and, when she tried to
squeeze in, grabbed her purse and gunned it.
</P>
<P>
   But the 30-something, would-be victim held on tight and was
dragged some 200 feet across the parking lot before Hawley,
apparently losing control of his vehicle, let go and sped off.
Police caught him a short while later.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old now stands accused of six robberies, including
one in which two elderly women were knocked down in a parking lot
and another where a 66-year-old woman was dragged by a car,
resulting in a broken wrist and chipped teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley has been jailed on charges of attempted robbery and
reckless endangerment.
</P>
</TEXT>
