<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Governor To Probe Fake Letter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Gov. Jeb Bush says a letter circulated
in Washington with his supposed signature is a fake, and he wants
investigators to find out who created it, a spokesman said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The letter expresses opposition to legislation before Congress
that would ban gambling on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some governors oppose the bill because it would not allow state
lotteries to sell tickets online, but Bush has taken no position on
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported the letter was addressed to Rep.
Cliff Stearns, R-Fla., and dated June 23. Stearns said he never saw
the letter, even though it has been circulating on Capitol Hill for
several days and is being used by opponents of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Justin Sayfie said Saturday that the governor had
asked the Florida Department of Law Enforcement to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The signature is not the governor's signature, and no one was
authorized to sign this letter on behalf of Governor Bush,'' Sayfie
said. ''At first glance, someone looking at it would have every
reason to believe it was a letter from Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   A public relations firm, Shandwick Washington, said it had asked
Bush's office for a letter giving his position on the legislation
and asked that it be addressed to a member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Shandwick represents eLottery Inc., a Connecticut company that
provides computerized services for state lotteries and would profit
from online sales of lottery tickets, the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   Shandwick spokesman Mark Day said the firm received the letter
in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had every reason to believe it originated in the governor's
office,'' Day said. ''It appeared to be on official stationery and
contained what appeared to be an official signature.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm has stopped circulating the letter, Day said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 1952 </TRAILER>
