<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canadian Tornado Kills Nine
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PINE LAKE, Alberta (AP) -- A tornado struck a campground about 90 miles north
of Calgary today, killing nine people, and sending more than 130 to the
hospital. The twister tossed trailers into a lake while devastating a crowded
campsite, forcing 400 to spend the night in temporary shelters, police said.
Divers searched submerged trailers for more victims.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombia Rebel Attack Kills 13 Cops
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A rebel missile attack on a small Andean mountain
town in southwest Colombia killed 13 police officers, officials said today. At
least five guerrillas also died in the fighting in Roncesvalles, a farming and
ranching town 105 miles from Bogota in Tolima State, national police chief Gen.
Alfredo Salgado reported. ''They picked on a handful of police who just trying
to maintain law and order,'' the general told Radionet radio. Army
rapid-reaction troops were sent to the area, where fighting continued Saturday
afternoon. But they were unable to enter Roncesvalles due to rebel mines, the
military said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban Exiles Launch Memorial Service
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Dozens of Cuban-Americans held a memorial service in
international waters off Havana today, throwing flowers from their boats to
remember 41 Cubans who drowned trying to leave the island six years ago. They
also joined in prayer for Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy found
floating alone off the Florida coast in November and whose journey home became a
half-year international custody battle. From their nine boats just outside
Cuba's territorial waters, about 12 miles from the communist island, the 60
boaters sang the Cuban national anthem and used mirrors to reflect flashes of
sunlight toward Cuba in an effort to communicate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tobacco Industry Readies for Appeal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Hundreds of thousands of sick smokers slated to receive a share
of the colossal $145 billion punitive damage award levied against the tobacco
industry may die before ever getting a penny from the tobacco companies. Moments
after yesterday's devastating verdict, tobacco companies promised to appeal. The
companies had sought a verdict of less than $400 million and claim the historic
damage award would put their industry out of business. They also say no final
order can be signed for decades until all smokers have their individual
compensation claims heard.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Barak, Arafat Meet
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat engaged with their delegations in informal
talks at the Mideast summit today as some delegates toured the Gettysburg
battlefield. ''The teams continued to meet informally and at times that involved
the leaders,'' said a White House spokesman who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. Unlike last night, there was no three-way meeting between the
leaders, he said. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was also involved in the
latest round of activity and a more formal meeting was planned for this evening.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iran Tests Ballistic Missile
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran test-fired the Shahab-3 missile Saturday, Tehran
television reported, the second trial in two years for the medium-range weapon
capable of reaching Israel or U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia. The state broadcast
said the test was in line with Iran's ''policy of strengthening its defense
capability on the basis of the principle of deterrence.'' In Israel, Deputy
Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh expressed concern Saturday about the missile test
''because Iran actively and relentlessly undermines the peace process through
various terrorist organizations.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Peacekeepers Freed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- In a rare display of force, U.N. troops on
Saturday launched a rescue mission that freed all 222 peacekeepers and 11
military observers trapped by rebels inside a U.N. base in eastern Sierra Leone,
U.N. officials said. The operation began about 6 a.m. in Kailahun, about 200
miles east of Freetown, when helicopters picked up the military observers.
Rebels fired at U.N. troops and British military Chinook helicopters supporting
the mission, said a senior peacekeeping officer, Indian Maj. Anthanarayan Arun.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lewis Knocks Out Botha in Round 2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Lennox Lewis used a three-punch combination to knock Francois
Botha to the canvas at 2:39 in the second round Saturday night, to retain his
WBC and IBF heavyweight titles. Lewis was in command the entire way, with Botha
pedaling backward almost from the opening bell.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Braves Defeat Orioles 7-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Tom Glavine pitched seven strong innings to earn his third
straight win and Javy Lopez homered as the Atlanta Braves finished a three-game
sweep of the Baltimore Orioles with a 7-3 victory today. The Orioles yielded 10
hits and committed three errors.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
