<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones, Greene Win Semifinal Heats  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- With some of the greatest sprinters in
history in attendance, Marion Jones and Maurice Greene took steps
Saturday toward winning the women's and men's 100 meters in the
U.S. Olympic track and field trials.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-driving Jones flew out of the blocks forcefully, then
wore down the field in winning her heat in 10.93 seconds to advance
to Saturday night's final.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jones' time was 0.01 seconds off her winning
performance in Friday's opening-round heats, she was just as
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Torri Edwards was a distant second at 11.14, followed by Chryste
Gaines (11.15) and Carlette Guidry (11.20).
</P>
<P>
   Inger Miller, the silver medalist to Jones in last year's World
Championships, won the other semifinal heat at 11.10, with Gail
Devers, the two-time world champion, the runner-up at 11.25.
</P>
<P>
   After the women sprinters competed, the sellout crowd of about
23,000 at Sacramento State's Hornet Stadium was introduced to Edith
McGwire, the 1964 Olympic 200 gold medalist and 100 silver
medalist, and Wyomia Tyus, the 1964 and 1968 Olympic 100 champion.
</P>
<P>
   Before the men ran, two more greats were introduced -- Bobby
Morrow, the 100, 200 and 400 relay gold medalist in the 1956
Olympics, and Jim Hines, the first man to break 10 seconds in the
100, the 1968 100 gold medalist and a member of the 400 relay team
that broke the world record.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inspired by their presence, the efficient Greene, the
world record-holder and two-time world champion in the 100, raced
to victory in 10.06, about 1&AMP;frac12; meters ahead of runner-up Ken
Brokenburr.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is attempting to become the seventh sprinter in Olympic
history to sweep the 100 and 200. He will compete in the 200 next
weekend against rival Michael Johnson, the world record-holder and
Olympic champion.
</P>
<P>
   Third-place finisher Dennis Mittchell, the 1992 Olympic bronze
medalist, was the most excited about reaching Saturday night's
final.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't stop me! I'm coming back!'' Mitchell exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   One of Greene's training partners, Jon Drummond, led all the way
in winning the other semifinal heat at 10.05.
</P>
<P>
   The men's shot put competition turned into one of the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Nelson, the former world junior champion, uncorked the
world's longest mark this year and his career best, 72 feet, 7
inches, on his final attempt.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Hunter, Jones' husband, finished second at 71-9, also a
personal best and also on his final attempt, and Andy Bloom took
third at 70-10&AMP;frac34;, another career best and also on his final try.
</P>
<P>
   In another final, Dawn Ellerbe, the American record-holder, led
a 1-2-3 finish by New York Athletic Club athletes onto the first
women's hammer throw team.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbe, who holds the U.S. best of 231 feet, 2 inches, had the
four-longest throws in the competition, all over 220-0, with her
best at 227-0.
</P>
<P>
   The muscular Ellerbe holds the world indoor best in the 20-pound
weight throw (77-6&AMP;frac14;) and is a five-time indoor champion. This was
her fifth national title.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Olympics are very important to me,'' Ellerbe said. ''It's
one of the things that kept me going all season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been chasing and chasing and chasing after it. I finally
caught my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Ellerbe on the Olympic team for the first women's hammer
throw at the games will be Amy Palmer and Jesseca Cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
