<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nelson Wins Shot Put Competition  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- On a day when Maurice Greene, Marion
Jones and Michael Johnson were the headliners, a hefty trio of shot
putters, including Jones' husband, stole a big share of the
spotlight in the U.S. Track and Field Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Led by surprising Adam Nelson, three throwers topped 70 feet
with personal bests Saturday in one of the most dramatic shot put
performances ever.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a 1997 Dartmouth graduate who until two weeks ago was
working 40 to 60 hours a week for a software company, uncorked a
worlds best of 72 foot, 7 inches on his last attempt, the longest
throw in the world this year. Only eight throwers have ever done
better.
</P>
<P>
   The drama wasn't over. On the last throw of the competition,
C.J. Hunter, Jones' massive husband, had a 71-9 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Bloom, who said he couldn't even walk 10 days ago because
of three displaced vertebrae and three displaced ribs, came out of
nowhere on his final throw of 70-10&AMP;frac34; for the third and final spot
on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't remember any time there was this kind of competition
in an event, and that includes all the events,'' Nelson said.
''It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bloom's throw, which came before those of Nelson and
Hunter, there was bedlam around the shot put ring. Nelson jumped on
Bloom's back. Hunter bumped chests with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Good things happen to good people,'' Hunter said, ''and he's a
good guy. It was just awesome to see him or anybody do what they
have to do when they have to do it. It was just great to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom knocked John Godina, a two-time U.S. champion and 1996
Olympian, off the team with his last throw. Godina, who still has a
chance to make the Olympic team in the discus, was fourth at 69-2&AMP;frac12;.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the meet grew longer I thought more and more that it was
going to hold up,'' Godina said of his best throw. ''Not because
anybody was incapable but just because of the day everybody was
having. Andy was having a terrible day up to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bloom knew he had one good throw in him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today somebody was smiling at me and I caught one,'' he said.
''I knew when I let go it was a long one.''
</P>
<P>
   The throws ranked first, second and sixth in the world this year
and established the U.S. contingent as perhaps the strongest its
been at the Olympics. But Bloom said no one should be surprised at
the dominant marks on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The winner was a little surprise, but if you didn't realize
the shot put was going to be where it was at, you haven't been
following track and field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who had the world's longest throw entering the meet,
said he could care less that he didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm shooting for Sydney,'' Hunter said. ''I've said 100 times
this year I don't care if I win any other meet, as long as I win
the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   The big day raised the specter of a possible U.S. sweep in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't care,'' the brutally honest Hunter said. ''I
want to win period. That's it. I don't even think about a sweep and
I hope these guys aren't thinking about it either. When I get to
Sydney, it's all about me. That's just how I feel. It's possible,
yeah, but so what?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
