<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Barak, Arafat Talk  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton and the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders moved Mideast peace talks back into high gear
late Saturday after the end of the Jewish Sabbath, and some
delegates took a somber tour of the Civil War battlefield in nearby
Gettysburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Following a day of informal meetings among the negotiators, some
of them involving the leaders, the pace was picking up, a White
House spokesman said in describing events on the fifth day of talks
at the Camp David presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we approach Day Six, we will look for further
intensification of these discussions,'' said the spokesman, P.J.
Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat had met until 1 a.m. EDT Saturday in only the
second three-way gathering at the talks that began Tuesday in
Maryland's Catoctin Mountains, 60 miles northwest of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The president met with Barak on Saturday evening, Crowley said,
and more meetings were possible later.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who sat in as lead
mediator for most of Thursday, was involved in the activity again
Saturday, including a meeting with Arafat. Mindful of the Jewish
Sabbath, which began at sundown Friday and ended at sundown
Saturday, negotiators kept to a slower pace.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a break from their own ancient quarrels, about 15 members
of the Israeli and Palestinian delegations had a firsthand look at
the scene of one of the greatest fraternal bloodlettings in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates took a two-hour tour of the Gettysburg
battlefield, about 15 miles from Camp David and the site of the
costly July 1863 engagement that was generally considered the Civil
War's turning point. None of the tour participants was a member of
the official negotiating teams, which are secluded at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The three leaders' 90-minute late-night session Friday in a
rustic cabin was an intimate gathering, held without delegation
members, the White House said. Other than the leaders, only
interpreters and note-takers were present.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton, Barak and Arafat first sat down together Tuesday,
the summit's opening day, Clinton has shuttled between the two
sides in talks described as contentious and difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Summit participants have agreed to disclose nothing of the
substance of the negotiations, but U.S. officials briefing
reporters have repeatedly used words like ''grappling'' and
''struggling'' to characterize the efforts. At one point, White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart described the issues as
''intractable.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Saturday whether the issues defied solution, Crowley said:
''I don't think any of us think they're impossible -- all of us
agree they are difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are deeply divided on key questions including the
boundaries of any future Palestinian state, the fate of several
million Palestinian refugees and status of Jerusalem, which both
sides claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   While the negotiators went about their task, Palestinian
demonstrators took to the streets in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
urging Arafat to stand firm. Israeli peace activists also gathered
in the Jerusalem suburb of Abu Dis to urge that Palestinians be
given a foothold in the disputed city.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinian demonstrators made thinly veiled threats of
violence should the summit fail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We give all our support to Arafat and the negotiators in Camp
David,'' said Shafik Tluly, a member of the leadership of Arafat's
Fatah faction. ''But if the summit fails, we are ready for all
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The length of the summit is still uncertain. Clinton is
scheduled to travel to Japan on Wednesday, but U.S. officials have
said that should not be considered a deadline for wrapping up the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak left home last Monday amid a political crisis triggered by
the collapse of his governing coalition. Israeli spokesman Gadi
Baltiansky told Israel radio that it would be difficult for the
prime minister to remain away from Israel for much more than two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is still our desire to see an agreement ... before the
president leaves for Tokyo,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Palestinian Authority: http://www.pna.org/mininfo/
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs:
http://www.israel-mfa.gov.il/mfa/home.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
