<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Politician Gunned Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALAGA, Spain (AP) -- A gunman firing at close range shot and
killed a ruling party politician Saturday night, as the victim's
wife and daughter watched, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The masked shooter fled on foot after the attack on Jose Maria
Martin Carpena, 49, a Malaga town councilor who belonged to the
center-right Popular Party of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   At the scene police found six 9 mm shells, a caliber often used
by the Basque separatist group ETA. But Interior Ministry
representative Jose Perez Velasco said it was too early to say if
the shooting was carried out by ETA.
</P>
<P>
   ETA -- the initials stand for Basque Homeland and Freedom in the
Basque language -- has killed some 800 people during a 30-year
campaign for independence of the Basque region of northern Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not rule out anything,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Carpena was shot in front of his apartment building as he
was preparing to get into his car with his wife and a young
daughter to attend an awards ceremony at which he was to be master
of ceremonies, Mayor Francisco de la Torre said on the CNN-Plus
television network.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors gathered outside the apartment building and shouted
''Murderers, Murderers!''
</P>
<P>
   ETA is blamed for five killings since ending a 14-month
cease-fire late last year. A car bomb blast Wednesday in Madrid
that injured nine people was attributed to ETA.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally the group has targeted military personnel and
police, although in the final few years before the recent truce it
often went after local councilors of the Popular Party, killing
eight since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these attacks took place in the Basque country itself
but in January 1998 in Seville an ETA gunman killed ruling party
councilman Alberto Jimenez Becerril and his wife Ascension. Both
were shot in the back of the head as they walked down the street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
