<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devers Out in 100 Meters  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Gail Devers missed out on a chance to
make Olympic history. Now she'll have to settle for trying to win
her favorite event.
</P>
<P>
   Devers, one of only two women to win the 100 meters in
consecutive Olympics, failed to qualify for the U.S. team for the
Sydney Games in that event when she finished fifth in the final
Saturday night in the U.S. trials.
</P>
<P>
   She finished in 11.149 seconds, less than two-hundredths of a
second behind third-place finisher Chryste Gaines. The top three --
Marion Jones, Inger Miller and Gaines -- made the team.
</P>
<P>
   Devers, who won gold in the 1992 Barcelona Games and the 1996
Atlanta Games, was trying to become the first woman to win the 100
in three straight Olympics. Only Wyomia Tyus, who watched the race
Saturday from the stands, also won consecutive golds in the 100 --
in 1964 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ''That opportunity to make history is gone. Now I have to
concentrate on the hurdles,'' Devers said.
</P>
<P>
   Devers always has considered the 100 hurdles her top race,
though she has failed to win an Olympic medal in that event. She
tripped at the final hurdle while leading by a comfortable margin
in Barcelona, and finished fifth. She was fourth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   She'll get a chance to make the Olympic team again in that event
starting next Saturday, when the first round of the hurdles is run.
The final is the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Devers also was a member of the U.S. gold-medal 400 relay teams
in Barcelona and Atlanta, and still could be selected for the relay
team.
</P>
<P>
   Devers, 33, nearly was forced to have her feet amputated and
missed a year of competition in 1989-90 because of Graves Disease,
a thyroid abnormality. Since returning to the track, she has been
one of the world's top sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she was bothered by a hamstring injury that kept her
out of competition until mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   She still adds a sense of style to the track. Her talon-like
fingernails were jet black at the trials, and she wore a diamond
necklace around her right thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Devers came tantalizingly close at Barcelona and Atlanta to
joining Fanny Blankers-Koen of Holland as the only Olympian to win
both the 100 and 100 hurdles in the same Olympics. Blankers-Koen
did it in London in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   This year, she won't even have a chance to try to pull off that
historic double.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course I would have loved to have been in the top three. It
wasn't my best race,'' she said. ''I will run some 100s later this
season, but not in Sydney. It will be interesting to be sitting in
the stands for the 100.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
