<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The show goes on for OpSail fireworks  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos xnlc 101 &AMP; 102
jcsyflsfonstv
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - Hundreds of thousands watched what
organizers called the largest fireworks display ever in New England
Saturday night as the grand finale to the four-day OpSail 2000
festival.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors braved the wind and rain Saturday for their last chance
to catch a glimpse of the tall ships.
</P>
<P>
   The weather threatened to snuff the fireworks display, but
organizers managed to pull off the show. OpSail spokesman John
Fleming estimated 300,000 attended the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It went off on time as planned,'' Fleming said. ''The
enthusiasm of the crowd certainly wasn't dampened.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said between 850,000 and 900,000 spectators attended
OpSail over four days.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been just excellent,'' Fleming said. ''It's just amazing
how well everything came together and how happy everyone seems.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Vanwey of Gales Ferry was among the spectators who was not
deterred by the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to stake our claim,'' Vanwey said. ''We got
umbrellas, tarps and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Sweeney of Niantic also came prepared. ''We did bring a
tent just in case it does rain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one ships from the United States, South America and Europe
took part in the event, which organizers hailed as a success for
this historic whaling town. Transportation, stressed by
unexpectedly large crowds on the opening day of the festival, ran
smoothly for the rest of the event and the Coast Guard reported no
serious boating accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The OpSail ships, which have also visited San Juan, Puerto Rico;
Miami; Norfolk, Va.; Baltimore; Philadelphia; and New York, will
head next to Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Amistad - a replica of the 19th-century schooner
whose cargo of African slaves revolted and won their freedom - was
feted in its home port of New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The Amistad sailed into the harbor after having participated in
OpSail in New York and New London. The vessel was greeted by a
flotilla of other ships and hundreds of drummers and singers,
including members of Boston's Sierra Leone Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone was the homeland of the 53 Africans who rebelled
aboard the original Amistad in 1839 and were freed after trials in
New Haven and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When the Amistad docked, it was blessed in a ceremony combining
West African and American traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day festival, featuring a bus tour of New Haven's
historical landmarks and cultural exhibits, will continue Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-15-00 2227 </TRAILER>
