<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gallo Blue Chip Wins at Meadowlands  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Heavily favored Gallo Blue Chip
took the lead with a three-wide move after the half-mile marker and
drew off to a 3&AMP;frac14;-length victory in the $1.15 million Meadowlands
Pace on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo Blue Chip covered the biggest mile race of the year for
3-year-old pacers in 1:50.4 in his third straight victory and sixth
in his last eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   In giving driver Daniel Dube his first Pace win, Gallo Blue Chip
paid $4.40, $3 and $2.80 and earned $575,000 for owner Martin
Scharf of Lawrence, N.Y. It was the second million dollar win for
the Mark Ford-trained gelding, who won the North America Cup at
Woodbine in Toronto on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Brett Pelling-trained entry of Astreos and High On Emotion
finished second and third, respectively, and paid $6.40 and $7.20.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo Blue Chip posted the fastest winning time in the three
eliminations heats for this race last weekend, but the big question
coming into the final was whether the gelded son of Magical Mike
could overcame the No. 9 post.
</P>
<P>
   He did with little problem.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the start, Dube moved Gallo Blue Chip quickly from
the outside and got him nestled in fourth place behind Ain't No
Stopn Him, Aces N' Sevens and Tyberwood, the 2-year-old pacer of
the year in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't No Stopn Him, driven by five-time Pace winner John
Campbell, held the early lead, before Cat Manzi moved Aces N'
Sevens to the front after the opening quarter mile.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Silverman tried to take the lead on the backstretch but
he couldn't get Tyberwood past Manzi and Aces N' Sevens.
</P>
<P>
   Dube moved Gallo Blue Chip to outside approaching the half mile
pole and then he boldly decided to move him to the lead three wide.
Once he was on top, he was never threatened. The gelding opened
five lengths on the field at the top of the stretch and coasted
across the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was frightened until the half,'' Scharf said. ''Once he
cleared to the lead, nobody can catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, a 29-year-old native of Lewisburg, W.Va., was relieved to
have the pressure of a long week over.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's really been more than I ever thought,'' Ford said. ''This
doesn't come along very often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Firepan ($12.20) won the $100,000 consolation of the
Meadowlands Pace, covering the mile in 1:50.4 with John Campbell in
the bike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-15-00 2246 </TRAILER>
