<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Royals 7, Brewers 4  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG TUCKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Joe Randa and Todd Dunwoody drove in two
runs apiece, enabling Jeff Suppan to get his first win since May 24
with a 7-4 victory over Milwaukee on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan (3-6), winless in a span of seven starts and two relief
appearances, was relieved by Ricky Bottalico after giving up a
one-out double to Geoff Jenkins and a single to Jeromy Burnitz in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In 7 1-3 innings, he surrendered four runs on 10 hits, with
seven strikeouts and no walks. He retired Ron Belliard on a ground
ball leading off the game and then struck out the next five
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Bottalico allowed a run on an infield out and got his sixth save
in 12 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who had lost nine of their last 11, jumped on Jimmy
Haynes (9-8) for five runs in the third. With the bases loaded and
one out, Mike Sweeney dropped an opposite-field single into shallow
right for one run.
</P>
<P>
   Two more runs scored when Jermaine Dye grounded to shortstop
Jose Hernandez, whose throw to first was high for an error. Then
Dunwoody's two-run single made it 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals loaded the bases again in the fifth on two walks and
Mark Quinn's infield single, and Randa grounded a two-run single
just past third baseman Charlie Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes, looking for his third straight victory, was charged with
seven runs in 4 1-3 innings, giving up eight hits with five walks
and two strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Belliard had an RBI double for Milwaukee in the third, then the
Brewers made it 5-3 in the fourth on Burnitz's 19th home run and
Hernandez's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Royals have won only one of their last nine series,
including this three-game set with the Brewers. ... The Royals
recalled LHP Tim Byrdak from Triple-A Omaha on Saturday and
optioned RHP Jeff D'Amico to the same club. ... The Brewers hit 10
doubles in the three-game series. ... Brewer 1B Tyler Houston took
a spill in the third. He jumped into the air trying to catch a high
throw from SS Hernandez and Jermaine Dye clipped his leg while
crossing the bag. Houston lay on the ground a couple of minutes but
stayed in the game. ... Royals 2B Luis Ordaz made a terrific play
on Hernandez's hot grounder in the sixth, diving to his right to
stop the ball and then getting the runner by a step.
</P>
</TEXT>
