<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Driver in Tenn. Crash Indicted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENTON, Tenn. (AP) -- A grand jury indicted a school bus driver
on three counts of vehicular homicide in a crash with a freight
train that killed three children at the Tennessee-Georgia border.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cloer, 34, was also indicted on four counts of reckless
aggravated assault and on charges of failing to stop a school bus
at a railroad crossing.
</P>
<P>
   She had picked up seven children the morning of March 28 and had
crossed from Tennga, Ga., into Polk County, Tenn., to turn around
when her school bus was hit by a CSX freight train at the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Highway Patrol and the National Transportation
Safety Board said in preliminary reports that Cloer did not stop at
the railroad crossing, even though school buses are required by law
to stop between 15 and 50 feet away. According to the NTSB
preliminary report, the freight train was traveling under the 60
mph allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Kayla Silvers, 6, and Daniel Pack, 9, died at the scene, and
Amber Pritchett, 9, died the following day. Four other children on
the bus, including Cloer's daughter, Kayli, were injured, as was
Cloer.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer surrendered Thursday after the Polk County grand jury's
indictment and was released on $5,000 cash bond. A hearing was
scheduled for Sept. 11, and a trial could come next year.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Finnell of Cleveland, a lawyer who represents Cloer, did
not return a phone call Saturday for comment on the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Martha West, said her daughter is distraught.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very upset. She just said, 'It was an accident,'''
West told Saturday's Chattanooga Times and Chattanooga Free Press.
''It's been really hard on everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
