<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Barak, Arafat Talk
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- After the end of the Jewish sabbath, President Clinton
and the Israeli and Palestinian leaders moved Mideast peace talks back into high
gear late Saturday, and some delegates took a somber tour of the Civil War
battlefield in nearby Gettysburg, Pa. Following a day of informal meetings among
the negotiators, some of them involving the leaders, the pace was picking up, a
White House spokesman said in describing events on the fifth day of talks at the
Camp David presidential retreat. ''As we approach Day Six, we will look for
further intensification of these discussions,'' said the spokesman, P.J.
Crowley.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombia Rebel Attack Kills 13
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Thirteen police officers defending a small Andean
mountain town from a rebel missile attack were executed after they surrendered,
officials said. The military said Saturday that 20 guerrillas died in an army
counterattack, but that report could not be independently confirmed. The police
officers fought all night, but their ammunition ran out after daybreak Saturday
in Roncesvalles, the besieged farming and ranching town 105 miles from Bogota in
Tolima State. When the officers tried to surrender the guerrillas walked into
the police barracks and shot them, national police chief Gen. Ernesto Gilibert
told reporters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Spanish Politician Gunned Down
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MALAGA, Spain (AP) -- A gunman firing at close range shot and killed a ruling
party politician Saturday night, as the victim's wife and daughter watched,
officials said. The masked shooter fled on foot after the attack on Jose Maria
Martin Carpena, 49, a Malaga town councilor who belonged to the center-right
Popular Party of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar. At the scene police found six
9 mm shells, a caliber often used by the Basque separatist group ETA. But
Interior Ministry representative Jose Perez Velasco said it was too early to say
if the shooting was carried out by ETA.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Peacekeepers Freed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. troops launched a rescue mission Saturday
that freed all 222 peacekeepers and 11 military observers trapped by rebels
inside a U.N. base in eastern Sierra Leone, U.N. officials said. In a rare
display of force, the operation began about 6 a.m. in Kailahun, about 200 miles
east of Freetown, when helicopters picked up the military observers. Rebels
fired at U.N. troops and British military Chinook helicopters supporting the
mission, said a senior peacekeeping officer, Indian Maj. Anthanarayan Arun.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Riots Engulf Hebron Jewish Enclave
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) -- The Jewish enclave in Hebron was engulfed for three
hours Saturday by rioting and fist fights between Jews and Arabs, an eruption
that could reverberate on the peace summit in Camp David. Five Palestinians were
hospitalized. Palestinians said the Jewish settlers, known to be the most
adamant opponents of Prime Minister Ehud Barak's peacemaking efforts, started
throwing stones at Palestinians in the afternoon, accusing them of disturbing
their Sabbath rest.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canadian Tornado Kills Nine
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PINE LAKE, Alberta (AP) -- A tornado struck a campground about 90 miles north
of Calgary today, killing nine people, and sending more than 130 to the
hospital. The twister tossed trailers into a lake while devastating a crowded
campsite, forcing 400 to spend the night in temporary shelters, police said.
Divers searched submerged trailers for more victims.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bahraini Royals Want Princess Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- Relatives of a Bahraini princess who eloped to the
United States with an American Marine want the teen-ager to return, saying they
are prepared to forgive her transgression, a government official said Saturday.
''Her family loves her and is really hoping that she will return home,'' an
Information Ministry official said of Mariam Al Khalifa, 19. The official
refused to comment when asked whether Al Khalifa's husband, Pfc. Jason Johnson,
also would be welcome.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wagner Card Auctioned for $1.1M
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A near-mint condition Honus Wagner card issued in 1909 by
the American Tobacco Company, fetched a winning bid of $1.1 million today on the
eBay online auction house. The winning bidder, whose identity was not released,
will pay $1.265 million, which includes a 15 percent buyer's premium. The card,
depicting the Hall of Fame Pittsburgh Pirates shortstop, is widely regarded as
one of the rarest and most coveted among collectors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubs' Sosa Ties DiMaggio on HR List in Win
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sammy Sosa tied Joe DiMaggio for 50th place on the career
home run list, hitting No. 361 as the Chicago Cubs beat the Minnesota Twins 8-4
tonight. Sosa connected in the second inning against Joe Mays for his 25th home
run of the season. He homered for the second straight day, and has hit four in
eight games.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
