<HEADLINE> Cohen: US To Take Australian Advice  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- The United States will look to
Australia for advice on how to handle the aftermath of the coup in
Fiji, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he would discuss the situation in Fiji when he holds
meetings with Australia's Defense Minister John Moore and Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Australia are among several nations which
have said they are considering diplomatic and trade sanctions
against Fiji in response to the coup and hostage crisis which
overthrew the elected government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will discuss what Australia thinks will be the best policy
to pursue,'' Cohen said. ''I think that Australia being closer,
much closer, to the situation, that we can perhaps work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen arrived in Australia late Saturday on the return leg of a
trip to China, his first since China agreed to resume military ties
with Washington, after having cut off all contact following the
U.S. bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in May
1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
