<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Fraud Gets Home Detention  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPPER MARLBORO, Md. (AP) -- A man considered the leader in a
financial scheme that defrauded more than 100 investors, including
author Tom Clancy, of about $8 million, was sentenced to 18 months
home detention because he is gravely ill.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Scott, 54, pleaded guilty in February to three counts of
conspiracy to misappropriate funds and two counts of securities
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He could have faced 11 years in prison and a $20,000 fine at his
sentencing Friday, but the two sides agreed on home detention and a
$10,000 fine because Scott suffers from severe kidney and liver
failure and must rely on his father for basic physical care.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this sort of unexpected factor of Mr. Scott's dying hadn't
entered into the picture, we would have pressed for a significant
jail term,'' said Carolyn H. Henneman, who argued for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Scott used his friendship with Clancy to persuade investors
across Maryland and Virginia to entrust their money to him, and
promised high returns of at least 15 percent. State investigators
said that he instead used the money for personal expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
